<HEAD>
<TITLE>TECHNOS Quarterly Biography - Melissa Koch</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>

<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>TECHNOS Quarterly</H1>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>For Education and Technology</H2>
<HR>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><I>Biography</I></H1>
<BR>
<P><IMG SRC="/journal/bios/mkoch.gif" align=right hspace=10><B>Melissa Koch</B> is a freelance writer and educational technology consultant who lives in San Francisco. Previously, as a research associate with The Edison Project, she coauthored &#147;Beyond the Lightbulb: The Promise of Technology in The Edison Project&#148; in the Spring 1993 issue of TECHNOS. Prior to Edison, she was an intern at the Federal Communications Commission and a production editor at M&T Publishing. Koch earned her bachelor's degree in English with an interdisciplinary concentration in gender and women's studies from Grinnell College and a master of arts degree in mass communications and telecommunications from Northwestern University.</P>


<HR>
