<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>STAYING POWER
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body text="#001831" link="#001831" vlink="#001831" background="../images/smallicons/Icon_frmbckgrd2.gif">
<p><br>
<center>
<table cellpadding="12" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600">
<tr>
<td>
<font face="Helvetica" size="6">STAYING POWER</font><br>




	As the prologue indicates, Mann Packing Company, Incorporated was founded in 1939 by H.W. "Cy" Mann.  Today, Mann Packing Company is the worlds largest shipper of fresh broccoli, as well as a shipper of over 35 different fresh vegetable commodities packed in 175 pack specifications. These packs are designed for the retail, wholesale, foodservice and export markets. 
	<p>
	In 1976 Mr. Mann welcomed Bill Ramsey and Don Nucci as partners in the firm. These partners in progress have not only led a quality team of personnel into building one of the most well-respected brands in the  fresh vegetable industry, but are champions on behalf of the industry and their community through the many additional activities they lend their leadership and support to.
<p>
<b>William "Bill" Ramsey</b><br>
	Ramsey joined Mann in 1955 where he directed growing and harvesting operations. Today he serves as company president and directs Manns quality systems in field-harvesting operations.
	<p>
	Ramsey is currently chairman of the board of Western Growers Association (WGA). WGA is an agricultural trade association whose members grow, pack and ship 90 percent of the fresh vegetables and about 60 percent of the fresh fruit and nuts in Arizona and California.
	<p>
	Besides being a WGA director for over 12 years, Bill is also a trustee for WGAs Pension Trust. His role as a member of WGAs Political Action Committee has taken him to Washington, D.C. on many occasions to testify before Congress on issues concerning American agriculture.
<p>
	 On a state level, the California Women for Agriculture have presented Bill with a Distinguished Service Award. He is also a honorary lifetime member of the California Teachers-Parents Association.
<p>
	Not many people in the local Salinas area can deny Bill Ramseys involvement in community issues. Ever since being voted the Salinas Jaycees outstanding young man of the year in 1967, Bills had a hard time learning to say "no." Hes a committed and driven man who believes strongly in family, community and charity. When he lends his time and support to a cause, you can bet its going to succeed.
<p>
	Bill is a past president of the Grower-Shipper Vegetable Association of Central California. He is a trustee of the Sun Street Alcohol Rehabilitation Center and has been a director of the California Rodeo for 15 years. He also served as Salinas City School Board president in 1987. His many years of service as a trustee for Hartnell Community College led them to thank him this past year by presenting him with an honorary degree. 
<p>
	Bill resides in Salinas with his wife Marlene Sbrana Ramsey. He has four children, three of which are involved at Mann Packing Company. Hes also the proud grandfather of eight lovely children.
<p>
<b>Don Nucci</b><br>
	Don joined Mann Packing Company in 1967 as office manager. He currently is secretary-treasurer for the firm and directs all sales and marketing.
<p>
	In 1984 Nucci was named THE PACKERs Produce Marketer of the Year. 
THE PACKER is the agricultural industrys Wall Street Journal  and each year honors an individual that has contributed significantly to the advancement of the marketing of fresh produce. The award is given on a national level at the Produce Marketing Association Convention and Exposition. In addition to this national recognition, Don served on the board of directors of the Produce Marketing Association for several years.
<p>
	Don also served on the board of directors for the Center for Produce Quality (CPQ) which was formed after the 1989 Alar Scare (a result of a story on 60 Minutes  regarding the safety of apples). CPQ was designed to unite the produce industry and allow them to respond quickly and accurately to misrepresentation of the safety of our food supply in the media. 
	<p>
	Don served as the founding president of the Central Coast Ag Task Force. He is also a past president of the Grower Shipper Vegetable Association of Central California. He also served on the board of directors of the Spreckels Union School District. 
<p>
	Don is a Salinas native which is evident in his involvement with the community. From coaching Little League to sponsoring scholarships for the children of farm-laborers, Don believes strongly in supporting education and recreational activities for the children and young adults of our city. His son and daughters may have played ball and graduated from local schools a few years ago, but Don can still be seen cheering in the booster section, coaching girls softball, and barbecuing tri-tip in the rain to raise money and support for his favorite teams.
<p>
	Don continues to reside in Salinas with his wife, Joan. He currently has three children working at Mann Packing and a fourth attending the University of Arizona. He also has a new grandson, Joseph Mathew Nucci.
<p>
	Mann Packing Company is a family-owned organization with roots running deep into the Salinas Valley. Weve been in business for 55 years and some of those years have been good, some of them bad. However, we love what we do and after 55 years weve discovered that what we do is not just run a company, but build families.
	<p>
	Weve also discovered that Mr. Mann is right. Teamwork is what has gotten us here and teamwork is what will take us into the future.  We are a proactive company. Our purpose is to be a leader in the fresh vegetable industry by providing a consistent supply of quality fresh vegetables through innovation, research, development, and marketing.
	<p>
	Being proactive is not just a clich, its a responsibility. A responsibility that we have not only to our 600-plus employees, but to over 30 families that grow crops for our company; to the service providers that paint our trucks and fix our forklifts; to the companies that supply us with cartons and computers; and to the hard-working, dedicated people of this community. Without them, we wouldnt be here.


<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
