</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Broccoli Facts(Production)
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body text="#001831" link="#001831" vlink="#001831" background="../images/smallicons/Icon_frmbckgrd2.gif">
<p><br>
<center>
<table cellpadding="12" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600">
<tr>
<td>
<font face="Helvetica" size="6">RESPONSE TO ADVERSITY/PROBLEM SOLVING</font><br>



	A willingness to listen and observe in an ever-changing, competitive environment is essential to success. Weve always taken a creative-problem solving approach to challenges we face - looking at them not as problems, but as opportunities in which to make things better.  We believe that obstacles are what you see when you take your eyes off the road. Following are some obstacles weve managed to avoid during our business history.
<p>
<b>Developing Markets</b><br>
	Growers and shippers in the Salinas Valley operate in a free-market environment - which means we are basically gamblers. There are no government subsidies for our crops or prorates. We basically go through a "daily auction" that establishes a market based on supply and demand. Grower-shippers invest tens of thousands of dollars in crops daily, not knowing if they will ever get a profitable return. 
	<p>
	Our goal is to ensure that the return is a profitable one for our growers and our company. Weve been able to do this by continually developing new and expanding markets for the crop. Some examples:
<p>
<b>Flight of the Freezers...</b><br>
	In 1968, 70 percent of our fresh broccoli volume was going to the frozen food market while 30 percent was directed to fresh. The early 1980s brought on an exodus of the freezers with companies like Green Giant/Pillsbury moving to Mexico. While operations and people can move to less-expensive growing regions such as Santa Maria or Mexico Salinas Valley acreage cannot. We had a responsibility to our growers to find a market for their crops - so we did.
<p>
	Today our company markets close to 15,000 acres of fresh broccoli to the domestic and international markets. We were able to find a "home" for the freezer broccoli while increasing our acreage because of new market developments. 
<p>
<b>Japan, Hong Kong, Singapore, Taiwan</b>
	In 1987 Mann Packing shipped our first box of broccoli to Japan. We took a unique approach to developing this market. Instead of trying to introduce the Japanese consumer to an American pack of broccoli (such as our traditional bunch) we duplicated a broccoli pack that was similar to one produced by Japanese broccoli growers.
<p>
	This pack takes extra time and attention since it features broccoli crowns that must be aesthetically pleasing and identical in size. We researched seed varieties that were suitable for producing uniform broccoli crowns and developed special cartons to protect the vegetable during long shipments. We also developed special cutting boards that attach to the harvesting machines.  These boards have a measurement device which enables the harvesters to measure each crown to the exact specification.
<p>
	Today our Pacific Rim distributor is one of our top three customers.  Shipper throughout the area have started to put up a pack similar to ours. We set the standard for exporting broccoli to Japan and look forward to expanding export-market opportunities.
<p>
<b>Broccoli Wokly Brings a Break-Through</b><br>

	Another new market development which enabled us to divert acreage away from freezer production was the foodservice market which was looking for a pre-cut, 
pre-washed fresh broccoli florette.
<p>
	Our first carton of broccoli florettes was shipped in 1983. What started on a metal table in the corner of our packing shed has turned into one of the largest fresh vegetable categories in the country.
<p>
	Today we produce over 120,000 pounds of broccoli florettes per day.  The florette development was soon followed by other innovative products such as: plate-ready broccoli spears, Hearts of Broccoli  and  MANNs Broccoli Cole Slaw. These products will be addressed in more detail under "Innovation and Creativity."
<p>
	In 1988 fresh-cut broccoli accounted for less than 5 percent of our sales. In 1993, 60 percent of our sales were fresh-cut.
<p>
<b>The White Elephant</b>
	In 1981 Mann Packing moved into a new, state-of-the art facility that was designed to facilitate the bunching of fresh broccoli.
<p>
	The number of companies shipping broccoli was limited since you needed a packing shed in which to bunch the broccoli. However, in the early 1980s harvesting developments allowed companies to bunch broccoli in the field. This brought on an influx of competition from other shippers and left us with a building that many in the industry referred to as "Manns white elephant." Our state-of-the art facility had suddenly become obsolete. At our lowest point, we had less than 100 people working in production.
<p>
	Mann Packing Company pioneered the markets for fresh-cut broccoli and today our "white elephant" is operating 20 hours a day, six days a week, year-round. With 600-plus employees, weve doubled our production capacity two years in a row and just finished an additional 30,000 square foot cooling expansion.
	



<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
