<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>INNOVATION AND CREATIVITY
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body text="#001831" link="#001831" vlink="#001831" background="../images/smallicons/Icon_frmbckgrd2.gif">
<p><br>
<center>
<table cellpadding="12" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600">
<tr>
<td>
<font face="Helvetica" size="6">INNOVATION AND CREATIVITY</font><br>





<b>Product</b><br>
	
	The principals at Mann Packing Company have a great deal of faith and trust in the people they employ. Following are some examples of what a few good employees can create when given the latitude to do so.
	<p>
	As previously stated, Mann Packing Company suddenly experienced a sharp increase in competition in the early 1980s when broccoli packing moved to the fields.
In order to stay competitive, employees at the company decided to  develop broccoli products that they could produce better, and more efficiently, than anyone else.
<p>
	David Stidolph, a consultant for the company for over 30 years, was brought in to develop a market for the fresh broccoli florette. Today Mann Packing ships dozens of different broccoli florette packs to the foodservice, wholesale and retail markets. Under the label "Broccoli Wokly" Mann Packing is the leader in broccoli florette production. Stidolph is highly regarded as "the father of the broccoli florette" throughout the produce industry and was named Produce Man for All Seasons by THE PACKER in 1993 for his work in this market development. 
<p>
	However, all of this fresh broccoli florette production turned into somewhat of a mixed blessing. You see, we were only shipping the top half of the broccoli plant. The bottom stalk was being hauled away by "cull" drivers and fed to dairy cattle. Mann Packing was faced with the challenge of developing a market for the delicious, edible stem of the broccoli plant. 
<p>
<b>Getting to the "heart" of the matter...</b><br>

	Under the guidance of David Stidolph, a team of marketing and production personnel at Mann Packing set forth on this challenging task. A competitor had previously diced and chopped the stalk and it was not received well by the industry. The team at Mann Packing knew we had to be better, we had to be different, and we had to get to the "heart" of the matter.
<p>
	Thus our Hearts of Broccoli line was born. We diced, we cut, and we sliced the stalk into various shapes and sizes. However, we stopped calling it the stalk of the broccoli and trademarked the phrase Hearts of Broccoli and Broccoli Hearts.  Suddenly we had a gourmet item that foodservice professionals were interested in!
<p>
	Aided by recipe development, marketing support and training, Mann Packing introduced the line to the trade. While we pinned the products to be perfect for institutional and non-commercial feeding establishments (such as schools, hospitals and prisons), little did we know that a long-time retail customer of ours would be interested in a pack that we put up "just for fun."
<p>
	We put the shredded broccoli hearts into a one pound bag and add carrots and red cabbage. Since broccoli is a cole crop, we called it MANNs Broccoli Cole Slaw. The retailer took some samples, put them on his shelf, and the rest is history.
<p>
<b>"Cool Slaw"</b><br>

	Today we produce over 90,000 pounds of MANNs Broccoli Cole Slaw every day. We get thousands of letters from consumers throughout the country applauding the virtues of this product. In fact, an informal survey of food editors by Food Business magazine named MANNs Broccoli Cole Slaw one of the best new food products - two years in a row!
<p>
	Weve hired 200 additional employees since introducing MANNs Broccoli Cole Slaw and have expanded the line to include a broccoli cole slaw with dressing, a Cauliflower cole slaw and a Rainbow Salad which includes broccoli cole slaw and cauliflower.






<p>
<b>Design</b><br>
<p>
	Mann Packing Company has a team of individuals nestled on a ranch near Chualar that design and fabricate some of the most advanced harvesting machinery in the world.
<p>
	Remote control operations... the ability to move at one-half mile per hour... elevating or lowering the cutting tables to the height of the plant so harvesters backs dont strain...these are just a few features created by Mann Packings team of engineers.  
<p>
	Four-way turn around capabilities allow for more efficient passings in the field. The powerful hydraulics proved to be a good investment for the company. Two Winters ago the Yuma growing region experienced devastating floods when the Gila River overflowed. Many companies could not get their machines into the field to harvest but we were able to.
<p>
	The processing plant on Harkins also has a team of engineers that are experts at the craft of "preventive maintenance." Machinery is designed and installed with checkpoints in place. Down-time is never good news to production managers. The refrigeration engineers must ensure that the 480 ton ice plant is able to produce just that, 480 tons, every day of the year. The bagging machines that produce 40-60 bags per minute must operate continuously so customers can get their product fresh and in a timely manner. This is no easy task. Proper design and implementation is crucial to running a productive and efficient "fresh" packing operation.
<p>
<b>Service</b>
	<p>
	Mann Packing Company is often referred to in the industry as the "unofficial broccoli board." We believe in promoting our commodity as much as our company and often supply generic broccoli information and photographs to food editors, dietitians, schools, home economists and hospitals throughout the country.

<p>
<b>Getting Broccoli into Schools...</b><br>

	Our "Camp Broccoli Wokly" program is designed to encourage fresh broccoli consumption among American school children. When our broccoli is featured on their "Menu Madness" schools are given free posters, Happy Camper stickers and Camp Counselor buttons. The schools are given credit for free nutritional education merchandise for each box of Mann Packing product served. Still in its infancy, the program is being well received by schools and has been successfully test-marketed in several regions of the country. 
<p>
<b>Helping the Environment...</b><br>

	Two years ago several employees were concerned with the amount of solid waste being produced by the Harkins Street plant. The principals agreed to form a Recycling Task Force to address the issue.
<p>
	The employees brought in a waste management expert that conducted a waste audit of the facility. They analyzed the waste stream from receipt to disposal and made recommendations on where the company could divert, reduce or eliminate waste.
<p>
	Today the plant currently diverts 82 percent of its solid waste away from landfills. The company has a part-time recycling coordinator on staff and participates in a national pallet pool to eliminate one-way pallets which are creating a huge environmental problem back East.

<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<center>
<a href="../images/footers/footer.map">
<IMG SRC="../images/footers/farmbutt.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
