<DOCOLDNO>IA045-000811-B012-370</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://broccoli.com:80/farm/sal_val_pisto_article.htm 204.157.36.20 19970118211627 text/html 6642
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Microsoft-IIS/2.0
Date: Sat, 18 Jan 1997 21:19:36 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Accept-Ranges: bytes
Last-Modified: Thu, 14 Mar 1996 19:54:57 GMT
Content-Length: 6444
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>sal val pisto article</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body text="#001831" link="#001831" vlink="#001831" background="../images/smallicons/Icon_frmbckgrd2.gif">
<p><br>
<center>
<table cellpadding="12" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600">
<tr>
<td>
<font face="Helvetica" size="6">Monterey County's Salinas Valley</font><br>



<P>
<font size="4"><b>&quot;Pastures of Heaven&quot;</font><BR>

<P>
<img align="right" border="1" src="../images/salinas/CA.jpg">
Mother Nature has painted a beautiful canvas across Monterey County's
Salinas Valley, located on California's Central Coast, just 15
miles east of Monterey Bay. Wrapped between the arms of the Gabilan
and Santa Lucia Mountain ranges, the Salinas Valley boasts a colorful
tapestry of 640,000 acres which produce wine grapes, fruits, vegetables
and floral products of unrivaled quality. 
<P>
Nobel Prize winning author John Steinbeck was born in Salinas
and referred to his home as &quot;pastures of heaven.&quot; Today
the Salinas Valley is an agricultural mecca producing over $2
billion worth of agricultural products annually. The nickname
bestowed on the valley decades ago has now become a fact. The
Salinas Valley is indeed, the Salad Bowl of the World.
<P>
The Salinas is a rich, flat valley 85 miles long and 15 miles
wide at the plain near its mouth. The most significant feature
of the Salinas Valley is the Salinas River. The watershed of the
river consists of 4,000 square miles, creating the largest intermontane
valley of the Coast Range. This river is the longest underground
river in North America, with nearly 80 miles of its 150 mile length
occurring below the surface. The Salinas River played a large
part in the settling of the Valley. Three of California's 21 missions
(Soledad, Carmel, San Antonio) were in the Salinas Valley, due
in part to the available water supply, suitable building sites
and sufficent grazing land.
<P>
<img align="left" border="1" src="../images/salinas/CA2.jpg">
When Father Junipero Serra established the Soledad and San Antonio
missions in the late 1770's, the Salinas Valley had been cattle
country where thousands of head roamed the unfenced land. In the
early 1860's the Salinas Valley economy was based on ranching.
Ironically, the Valley was deemed worthless for farming. Between
1861 and 1865 the Valley experienced years of extreme drought,
followed by unprecedented flooding and cold weather, killing off
90 percent of the county's tens of thousands of black Spanish
cattle. What proved to be a disaster to the ranchers became a
blessing to the farmers. The floods washed rich top soil from
the hills and deposited them on the valley floor. River silt further
enriched the land and from 1862 to 1875, acres under cultivation
more than tripled and wheat grew from 26 percent share of the
crops to 75 percent.
<P>
Some significant changes began occurring in the Valley's agricutural
patterns. Sugar beets had been planted on over 23,000 acres and
dry beans and peas occupied another 18,000. The year 1919 brought
even more changes. With the fading of World War I, so did the
demand for dry beans and sugar. Sugar beet acreage increased at
the time only to be met by a decrease in demand due to the end
of World War I. This caused prices to fall and the spread of &quot;curly
top disease&quot; and a decline in seed quality also impacted
sugar beet production. 
<P>
Artichokes began to fill the void left by the reduction in sugar
beet cultivation in the Northern end of the Salinas Valley. The
artichoke fields surround a small town called Castroville which
claims to be the &quot;artichoke&quot; center of the world. 
<P>
While artichokes then and now play an important role in agriculture
production, it was iceberg lettuce that would lead an agricultural
revolution in the rest of the area. Consider this: in 1922 approximately
300 acres of lettuce were planted around Salinas. By the end of
the decade 43,000 acres of the Salinas Valley were growing this
&quot;green gold.&quot;
<P>
<img align="left" border="1" src="../images/salinas/CA3.jpg">
The Valley today is still comprised of family ranches that have
been cultivated for many generations. The majority of these growers
produce crops for larger &quot;shippers&quot; who bring the farmer's
crops to market. These markets could be as close as the store
in downtown Salinas or as far away as Saudi Arabia, Singapore,
Switzerland, Japan or Indonesia. In fact, there is little doubt
that the produce in <I>your </I>local grocery store was grown
in the Salinas Valley.
<P>
Each year farmers in the Salinas Valley produce 12,500 tons of
tomatoes, 15,000 tons of strawberries. Do you like to eat salads?
Last year farmers in the Salinas Valley produced over 82,000 tons
of lettuce! 
<P>
Broccoli is the second largest crop with close to $271 million
dollars worth produced annually. In fact, there are 47 crops,
from grapes to brussel sprouts, that bring in over one million
dollars annually to Monterey County.
<P>
Of course, all of this money is not seen by the farmers who must
invest in the seed, fertilizer, water and cultivation before the
crop is ever brought to market. If there is an excess in supply,
the market is low and farmers often sell their crops at a loss.
Worst yet, if there is a problem with pests or weather, entire
crops can be lost and the farmer will never see a return on his
or her investment.
<P>
<img align="right" border="1" src="../images/salinas/CA4.jpg">
<br>
Unrivaled growing conditions, fertile soil and an ideal climate,
helped make the Salinas Valley what it is today. During peak growing
season, over 1,000 refrigerated trucks leave the area daily to
deliver fresh, wholesome produce to markets all over the world.

<P>
So the next time you step into your local grocery store and take
a look around that colorful, fresh produce department, or the
next time you sit down at a restaurant and bite into a crunchy
Caesar Salad, think of Monterey County's Salinas Valley, and all
of the families who work so hard to bring fresh, quality produce
to you.<BR>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
