<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>sal val trivia</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body text="#001831" link="#001831" vlink="#001831" background="../images/smallicons/Icon_frmbckgrd2.gif">
<p><br>
<center>
<table cellpadding="12" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600">
<tr>
<td>
<font face="Helvetica" size="6">Salinas Valley Trivia</font><br>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>What &quot;nickname&quot; does the Salinas Valley have and
is often referred to?
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>The Salad Bowl of the World.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>What is unique about the Salinas Valley River?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Longest underground river in America with nearly
80 miles of its 150 mile length occurring below the surface. 
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>What is the size of the Salinas Valley?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Consists of 640,000 acres. The watershed of the Salinas
River consists of 4,000 square miles. The valley is roughly 80
miles long stretching from Castroville in the north to San Ardo.</FONT>
<P>

<B>How many of California's missions (founded by father Junipero
Serra) are located in the Central Coast area? Can you name them?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Four missions are in or near the Salinas Valley.
San Juan Bautista, Soledad, San Antonio and Carmel. Father Serra's
resting place is in the Carmel Mission.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>What was the main industry in the Salinas Valley during the
late 1700's and 1860's?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>The Salinas Valley was Cattle Country where thousands
of head roamed the unfenced land. Early economy was based on cattle farming. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>What natural events occurred between 1861 and 1865 that proved
to be a bane to the ranchers and a blessing to the farmers?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Years of extreme drought were followed by unprecedented
flooding and cold weather, killing off 90 percent of the county's
tens of thousands of black Spanish cattle. The floods washed rich
top soil from the hills and deposited them on the valley floor.
River silt further enriched the land. From 1862-1875, acres under
cultivation more than tripled, and wheat grew from a 26% share
of the crops to 75 percent.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<b>What crops where grown in the Salinas Valley in the
early 1900's (think Spreckels)?</b>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Sugar beets had been planted on over 23,000 acres
and dry beans and peas occupied another 18,000.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>What crops first emerged in the 1920's?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Artichokes filled an agricultural void in the northern
Salinas Valley left by declining sugar beet cultivation. It was
iceberg lettuce that would lead an agricultural revolution in
the rest of the area.<U> In early 1922, approximately 300 acres
of lettuce were planted around Salinas. By the end of the decade,
43,000 acres of the Salinas Valley were planted in lettuce! <BR>
<BR>
</U></FONT>
<P>
<B>How was produce transported throughout the country in the early
days?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>By 1939 over 1,000 railcars of artichokes, 24,000
cars of lettuce and 7,000 cars of other vegetables were shipped
from the Salinas Valley. This region now represented the greatest
production of row crops in the country. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>What was invented in 1947 that boosted the lettuce industry?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Vacuum cooling.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>What makes the Salinas Valley such a great place to farm?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Unrivaled growing conditions. Fertile soil and an
ideal climate. Today, over 35 crops gross almost two billion dollars
annually. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B>During peak growing seasons, how many trucks loaded with produce
leave the Salinas Valley daily?</B>
<P>
<FONT color="navy" SIZE=3>Over 1,000.</FONT> 

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<center>
<a href="../images/footers/footer.map">
<IMG SRC="../images/footers/farmbutt.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
