<html>

<head>
<!-- MANN'S BROCCOLI, PREPARATION, Dreated on 5/1/96 by gavdw  -->
<!--  Last Edited 8/12/96 by gavdw  -->
<title>Broccoli Handling/Storing Tips</title>

</head>
<body>
<body text="#001831" background="../images/smallicons/Icon_mombckgrd4.gif">
<br>
<center>

<table width="600" bgcolor="#FFEBD7" border="1" bordercolor="#00672E" cellpadding="12" cellspacing="0">

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<center>
<font face="Helvetica" color="#00672E" font size=7>
Handling & Storing Tips
</font>
</center>
<font size="3"><b>
<p>
<font size=+3><font color="#00672E">B</font></font>roccoli stalks should have tight and compact bud clusters with an even dark green or purplish green color. The stalk should be easy to pierce with a fingernail.  Different varieties of broccoli come in colors ranging from deep sage green to purplish green.  Broccoli stems should be a lighter green than the buds, tender and slightly moist.  Avoid broccoli stalks with yellowed or open bud clusters or stems that are hard and dry.  Also avoid broccoli with soft, slippery water-soaked spots of the bud cluster. Broccoli is usually sold by the one-pound bunch; check the weight to get the best value. The size of the head has no relation to eating quality. Store in plastic bag in refrigerator crisper.
<p>
<font size=+3><font color="#00672E">B</font></font>roccoli crowns are becoming more popular and provide more accurate portion control for the consumer and less waste. They are sold by the individual piece or by the pound.
<p>
<font color="#00672E"><font size=+3>B</font></font>roccoli florettes are also sold in stores loose in baskets for consumers to choose or packaged in a breathable bag. Broccoli florettes in a bag should have no brown discolaration at the cutting point and should look and smell fresh. An expiration date should be on the package.
<p>
<font size="3"><b>
<font size=+3><font color="#00672E">B</font></font></font>efore using broccoli that is not already packaged washed and ready to eat, clean by rinsing (not soaking) the broccoli and trim the main stem slightly at the bottom.

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<a href="../images/footers/footer.map">
<IMG SRC="../images/footers/kitbutt.gif" ismap border="0"></a>


</center>



	
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B23-106</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA045-000811-B013-313</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://broccoli.com:80/kitchen/cooking.htm 204.157.36.20 19970118212149 text/html 5403
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Microsoft-IIS/2.0
Date: Sat, 18 Jan 1997 21:25:07 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Accept-Ranges: bytes
Last-Modified: Mon, 19 Aug 1996 17:04:52 GMT
Content-Length: 5205
</DOCHDR>
<html>

<head>
<!-- MANN'S BROCCOLI, COOKING, Created on 7/1/96 by gavdw  -->
<!--  Last Edited 8/19/96 by gavdw  -->
<title>Broccoli/Cooking</title>

</head>
<body background="../images/smallicons/Icon_mombckgrd4.gif">

<center>
<br>
<table width="600" bgcolor="#ffffff">

<tr>

<td>


<table width="600" bgcolor="#ffffff" border="0" bordercolor="#000000" cellpadding="12">

<tr>

<td valign="top" width="250"><p><br><p><br>
<img src="../images/smallicons/pot.jpg"><br>

</td>


<td width="350" valign="top">
	<font size="4" color="green">
	<b>STOVE TOP PREPARATION:<br>
	</font>
<font size="2" color="#000000"><b>
	Because of its strong characteristic flavor, broccoli should be cooked uncovered in a large quantity of boiling water.  Fresh broccoli requires 3 to 6 minutes cooking time in rapidly boiling water. Broccoli should only be cooked until it turns a bright green and is still crisp and tender.It should then be drained and rinsed with cool water to stop the cooking process. Broccoli that is overcooked will turn a dark khaki green (almost) gray and will not look or smell pleasing. The biggest mistake people make with broccoli is overcooking it.
	<p>
	If steaming the product on your stovetop leaves an undesirable odor, place a drop of dry vermouth in the pot to hinder the odor. 
	</font>
<hr width="350">
	<font size="4" color="green">
	<b>MICROWAVE PREPARATION:<br>
	</font>
<font size="2" color="#000000"><b>
	Broccoli is cooked beautifully in the microwave. Simply place cut broccoli in a microwave safe dish with one inch of water. Cover bowl with saran wrap or glass lid and place in microwave for 3 to 4 minutes (time will vary depending on power of the microwave and the amount of broccoli youre preparing).Remove and rinse with cold water (be careful of hot steam that might burn).
	<p>
	Some fresh broccoli florettes come washed and ready to eat in a microwavable bag. Read the package instructions for more details.
	</font>

</td>

</tr>
<!--------------------------------->
<tr>
<td colspan=2>

<table width="575" bgcolor="#000000" cellpadding="7">
   <tr>
    <td valign="top"><center>
     <font size="5"color="#ffffff">
	<b>COOKING TIPS</b>
	</font></center>
     </td>
    </tr>
   </table>


</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top"><b>


	<i><b><font size="4" color="navy">
	The Steam Method:</font></b></i>
	<br>Place fresh broccoli in boiling water for approximately 6-8 minutes. For tender crisp vegetables steam for 4-6 minutes. Frozen broccoli cooks in 8 to 10 minutes.
	<br><i><b><font size="4" color="navy">
	The Saucepan Method: </font></b></i> 
	<br>Place broccoli in a saucepan with one inch of boiling water and one-half teaspoon of salt.  Cook with cover off the first five minutes, and then cook covered 10 to 15 minutes or only until crisp-tender.  Or, if desired, leave cover on during the entire cooking period, but lift the lid three or four times to permit the gases to escape, and thus protect the green color of the vegetable.  

	<i><b><font size="4" color="navy">
	<br>Aluminum, stainless steel, enamel and glass</font></b></i> 
	<br> are the better utensils for cooking fresh broccoli and retaining nutrients. Iron pots can give you the benefit of iron mineral content, but they will rob you or decrease the benefits of Vitamin C.
</td>

<td colspan=2 valign="top"><b>
	<i><b><font size="4" color="navy">
	In general,</font></b></i> 
	<br> cook as briefly as possible in a small amount of water, both to preserve the crisp texture and to conserve nutrients.
	<br><i><b><font size="4" color="navy">
	For your convenience,</font></b></i> 
	<br> Manns fresh-cut vegetables are available in microwaveable bags!. With a fork or knife, simply poke a few holes in the bag.  Since microwave power varies, the following times are approximate.
	<i><b><font size="4" color="navy">
	<br>For tender-crisp vegetables:</font></b></i>
	
	<br>8 oz package = <br>microwave on high for 3-4 minutes<br>
	16 oz. package = <br>microwave on high for 4-6 minutes<br>

	Carefully remove bag from microwave -as it will be hot!  To remove vegetables from bag, let stand for approximately 1 minute and cut bag with a knife.

	</font>

</td>
</tr>

<!----------------------------------->



<tr>
<td colspan=2><b>

  <table width="575" bgcolor="#000000" cellpadding="7">
   <tr>
    <td valign="top"><center>
     <font size="5"color="#ffffff">
	<b>HANDLING/SERVING TIPS</b>
	</font></center>
     </td>
    </tr>
   </table>
	Before using, wash by rinsing (not soaking) the broccoli and trim the main stem slightly.  (If fresh broccoli is soaked, it may lose the benefits of Vitamins B & C.) Cut into florettes or for a crunchy snack, peel stem and cut into coins or sticks.  
	<p>
	Broccoli may be served raw with a dip or cooked and topped with sauces or lemon juice.  Great over rice, in salads, quiche, soups or any of your favorite dishes.

	</font>
</td>
</tr>

</table>


</td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>

<a href="../images/footers/footer.map">
<IMG SRC="../images/footers/kitbutt.gif" ismap border="0"></a>

</center>

</body>
</html>
