<DOCHDR>
http://broccoli.com:80/kitchen/presentation.htm 204.157.36.20 19970118212209 text/html 3455
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Microsoft-IIS/2.0
Date: Sat, 18 Jan 1997 21:25:27 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Accept-Ranges: bytes
Last-Modified: Fri, 15 Mar 1996 15:46:43 GMT
Content-Length: 3257
</DOCHDR>
<html>

<head>
<!-- MANN'S BROCCOLI, Presentation, Dreated on 8/5/96 by gavdw  -->
<!--  Last Edited 8/12/96 by gavdw  -->
<title>Broccoli Presentation Tips</title>

</head>
<body>
<body background="../images/smallicons/Icon_mombckgrd4.gif">
<br>
<center>

<table width="600" bgcolor="#FFEBD7" border="1" bordercolor="#00672E" cellpadding="12" cellspacing="0">

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<center>
<font face="Helvetica" color="#00672E" font size=7>
PRESENTATION TIPS
</font>
</center>
<p>
<font size="3"><b>
<font size="4">
<b>Serving Broccoli "Cold"</b></font><br>
When serving broccoli raw in a vegetable tray or cold salad (such as pasta), try blanching or steaming the product very lightly (under one minute) then immersing in ice cold water to stop the cooking process. The broccoli will be a beautiful, brilliant green. The broccoli will also be tender-crisp with a more pleasing flavor. 
<p>
<blockquote><b>Note: </b>  <br><i>This process should only be done when serving the broccoli within the next two 	hours. If left  overnight the broccoli will turn a dull green and not taste as fresh. 
</i></blockquote><p>
<font size="4"><b>Serving Broccoli "Hot"</b></font><br>
Broccoli is best prepared by blanching or steaming the product lightly (three to four minutes maximum). Blanching may be done on the stove top in boiling water or steamed in a microwave or commercial steamer. It is important to "shock" the broccoli after this process so the cooking stops. If broccoli just sits hot in a strainer it will continue to cook, causing the color to fade and the texture to become soft. Broccoli is ideal when prepared
 tender-crisp or al dent which means "to the touch." This not only retains nutrients but provides beautiful color and texture to any recipe.
<p>
<font size="4"><b>Save Those Broccoli Stems!</b></font><br>
When preparing fresh broccoli dont forget the nutritious, tender stalk (or Hearts of Broccoli or Broccoli Hearts which is what we call them here at Mann). We use shredded hearts of broccoli in our broccoli cole slaw which is one of the fastest selling vegetable items in the country!
<p>
Try creating some Broccoli Heart recipe applications in your kitchen at home! Trim about half an inch off the bottom of the stalk and dice into small pieces as a more nutritional alternative to diced celery. Use in stuffings, tuna or chicken salad. Crunchy and nutritious!
You may also cut the stalk into "broccoli sticks" but use them quickly because they will start to curl eventually (unless you want to serve "broccoli curls" another good idea!).  
The stalk is also ideal for cutting into "coins" and adding to salads, stir frys, pasta or dip.
<p><blockquote>
<b>Note: </b><br><i> Many folks belive you have to peel the stalk before using. While the inner portion
	is certainly more tender, our experience has shown that the light layer of skin
	on the stalk is similar to the skin on an apple or potato. Its holding in nutrients
	and does not create a fiborous barrier (especially when cooked).

</i>
</blockquote>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<a href="../images/footers/footer.map">
<IMG SRC="../images/footers/kitbutt.gif" ismap border="0"></a>


</center>

	
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
