<title>Quick Nutritional Facts</title>

</head>

<body background="../images/smallicons/Icon_umbckgrd.gif" bgcolor="#FFEBD7">
<br>
<center>
<table bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600" cellpadding="12" border="0">

<tr>
<td>
  <table cellpadding="8" bgcolor="#000000" width="580">
  <tr>
  <td align="center">
<font size="6" face="Helvetica" color="#ffffff"><b>Nutrition Facts: The New Label</b></font>
  </td>
  </tr>
  </table>
<br>
Wondering whats in all those little snacks youve been eating?  Hopefully, by now,  everyone looks at the back of a food products label before purchasing.  The "Nutrition Facts" labeling, found on the label of all food products since May 8, 1994,  was designed by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and the Food Safety and Inspection Service of the U.S. Department of Agriculture in correlation with multiple consumer studies.  The new label was designed to make reading nutritional information on product packages easier for consumers and in a language they understand.

Before the new labeling was introduced manufacturers could put information such as saturated fat and cholesterol on the labels voluntarily, but facts such as dietary fiber and sugars were not allowed.  
<p>
 The purpose of the new "Nutrition Facts" labeling is to clear up confusion that has prevailed in food labeling for years, to help consumers choose more healthful diets, and to offer an incentive to food companies to improve the nutritional qualities of their products.

<p><br>

<center><img src="../images/label.jpg"></center>
<p><br>

<!---------------------Next Section-------------------------->
<b><font size=4 color="#001831">Nutrition Facts</font></b><br>
Serving Size 1 cup (228g)<br>
Servings Per Container 
<p><p>

<ul>
<li>new heading signals a new label (point out new heading)
<p>
<li>More consistent serving sizes, in both household and metric measures, replace those that used to be set by manufacturers. (point to serving size on label)
 <p>
<li>New mandatory component helps consumers meet dietary guidelines recommending no more than 30 percent of calories from fat. (point to calories from fat on label )		
<p>				
<li>% Daily Values shows how a food fits into the overall daily diet ( point to % daily values)
</ul>

<ul>
<li>Nutrients required on nutrition panel are those most important to the health of todays consumers, most of whom need to worry about getting too much of certain items (fat, for example), rather than too few vitamins or minerals, as in the past. (point out bracket covering fat down to the vitamin and minerals)
<p>
<li>Reference values help consumers learn good diet basics.  They can be adjusted, depending on a persons calorie needs. (point out the reference values on the label)
<p>
<li>Conversion guide helps consumers learn caloric value of he energy-producing nutrients. (point to the conversion factor section of the label)
</ul>

<p><br>
  <table>
  <tr>  
<td> 
<font color="#001831">METRIC CONVERSION CHART</font>
   </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
   <td>
