  240 mL1 <br> 30 ml     <br>                                                                         28 g
   </td>   
   </tr>
   <tr>
   <td colspan="2">
tsp = teaspoon <br> 
 tbsp = tablespoon<br>
fl oz = fluid ounce<br>
oz = ounce<br>
mL = milliliter<br>
g = gram
   </td>
   </tr>
   </table>
  <p><br>

<table cellpadding="8" bgcolor="#000000" width="580">
  <tr>
  <td>
<font size=5 face="Helvetica" color="#ffffff"><b>Nutrition Facts: Relevance to Produce</b></font>
  </td>
  </tr>
  </table>
<p>
The new food label rules effect the fresh fruit and vegetable industry in a variety of ways.  Fresh fruits and vegetables treated with post-harvest wax or resin coatings must indicate the presence of coatings following the FDAs new rule, for example, with apples. The labeling for fresh fruit and vegetables is covered by a <b>voluntary</b> program following  guidelines issued by FDA in November 1991.  Under this rule it is the responsibility of the <b>retailers</b> to provide nutrition information for the twenty most frequently consumed varieties of fresh fruit  and twenty most frequently consumed varieties of fresh vegetables.  This information should be available to consumers at the point of purchase in the form of posters, brochures, notebook, etc.
<p>
When considering the fresh-cut packaged category of fresh fruits and vegetables, it is still voluntary for manufacturers to provide nutritional labeling.  The exception of this rule is when another product is in the package.

For example, with <b>Manns Broccoli Wokly with Cheese</b>, the nutritional information of the cheese is required on the package.  Fortunately, most of the manufacturers place the Nutrition Facts on all consumer packages.
<p>
Nutrient content claims (e.g. LOW FAT, GOOD SOURCE OF VITAMIN C, HIGH FIBER) can be made only if the product meets composition requirements established by the FDA.  The FDA has reviewed research supporting individual claims for specific product categories, and then grant permission to companies to make the claim.  If it fits the composition requirements for the claim, the company can use it on their packaging. For example, <b>broccoli</b>  is allowed to add the health claims between:<b> vegetables and cancer, fat and cancer, saturated fat and cholesterol/coronary heart disease, and sodium and hypertension.</b>  These are established and approved by the FDA.
<p><br>

  <table cellpadding=8 width=500 border=2 bordercolor="#000000">
  <tr>
  <td>
<font size=+1 face="helvetica" color="#001831"><b>What Do Consumers Think About Nutrition? </b></font>
<p>
<b>Facts:</b>
<ul>
	<li> 3 out of 4 consumers say they are aware of the governments guidelines 	recommending the number of daily servings of fresh fruits and vegetables.
								<br>
							<i>Fresh Trends, 1995</i>
	<p>
	<li>  When reading labels, 87% of Americans are concerned with the fat content of 	food while half pay close attention to the cholesterol.
						<br>
							<i>Food Institute Report, 12/04/95</i>
</ul>

  </td>
  </tr>
  </table>


</td>
</tr>

