<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Nutrition Lesson Plans</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>
<BODY text="#001831" link="#001831" vlink="#001831" background="../images/smallicons/Icon_umbckgrd.gif">

<P>
<CENTER>

<TABLE cellpadding="12" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600">
<TR>
<TD>

<table cellpadding="8" bgcolor="#000000" width="575" height="50">
  <tr>
  <td>

<B><FONT face="Helvetica" color="#ffffff" SIZE=6>Nutrition Lesson Plans<BR>
</FONT></B>

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
 

<u><B><FONT SIZE=4>Parents and Educators </FONT></B></u><br>


There is a growing concern for the need to educate children on how to eat and live healthy lifestyles. The Center of Science in the Public Interest (CSPI) reported on June 3, 1991 that more than 90% of children's television advertisements on a typical Saturday morning promoted food of low nutritional value. <BR>

<P>
One of the most critical ages is when the child is becoming a teenager, or their pre-teen years. At this age, children become more responsible in helping out in the household. It is also a period where children begin to develop life-long habits. That is why it's important to emphasize healthy eating habits, outdoor/indoor physical activities, and limited television viewing, as well as junk foods and fast foods in moderation. Parents are the role models for children and they will follow in their footsteps. Here's a few ways to get you and/or your family on the right track.<BR>

<P>
There are a lot of nutritional lesson plans already set up and ready to go for kids, it's just the matter of bringing them into action. The following are some educational resources for parents and educators to teach children healthy lifestyle habits in a fun and interesting way. <BR>
<BR>
<img src="../images/bullets/redline.jpg">
<P>

  <table cellpadding="8" width="575" height="50">
  <tr>
<td>
<img src="../images/5-a-dayhealth.jpg">
</td>
  <td>
<u><B><FONT SIZE=4>5 A DAY- for Better Health</FONT></B></u>
<br>
The Produce for Better Health Foundation and the National Cancer Institute have developed a nationwide program aimed at consumers to get everyone to eat at least five servings of fruits and vegetables a day. A majority of states have their own programs set up through their Department of Health Services offering a variety of educational resources for everyone. The following are some facts gathered by the California Department of Health Services for their 5 A DAY Power Play Campaign aimed at targeting California's 9 to 11 year olds with nutrition education.

  
  </td>
  </tr>
  </table>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <table cellpadding="8" width="575" bordercolor="#000000" border="1" height="70">
  <tr>
  <td>
<center>
<b><FONT SIZE=5>Fast Facts
<br>
on 
<br>
California's 5 A DAY-Power Play Campaign <BR>
</FONT>
</center></b>
  </td>
  </tr>
  </table>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1>What health problems of children are associated with a poor diet?<BR>
</B></font>

Poor diet contributes to obesity, high blood cholesterol, anemia, susceptibility to lead poisoning, low self esteem, and poor school performance. Good dietary habits may give kids a head start in reducing the risk of chronic diseases later in life (like certain common cancers, heart disease, hypertension, diabetes, and osteoporosis). <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1>Why do children need to eat fruits and vegetables?<BR>
</B></font>

Fruits and vegetables are the major dietary sources of many nutrients essential to growth and development, such as vitamins A, C, and folate, as well as dietary fiber and other protective plant substances. It is recommended that all children over the age of two years eat a low-fat, high fiber diet high in fruits and vegetables. <BR>


<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1>How many fruits and vegetables should children be eating?<BR>
</B></font>

The American Academy of Pediatrics, the National Academy of Sciences, the U.S. Departments of Health and Human Services, the U.S. Department of Agriculture, the California Department of Health Services, and the California Department of Education all recommend that kids eat 5 servings or more of fruits and vegetables every day. Five servings a day is a national health goal for the year 2000. A recent study found that fourth, fifth, and sixth graders in California eat a little over 3 servings daily -- too few for good health.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1>Why do children need to have a special program?<BR>
</B></font>

Kids will not respond to a health campaign that looks like one for adults. They love humor, action, color, music, fantasy, and competition. Their authority figures are older kids, cool kids (like themselves), and celebrities they admire. They look closely at style and fashion, and they want to know what the immediate benefits are. They can be reached best through radio, TV, and popular culture, like music and sports.<BR>

<P>
Kids' fruit and vegetable preferences are also different. They like fruit. But in vegetables they that what they think is hard, tough, bland, or mushy. They like distinct texture, finger foods, strong flavors like Chinese, Mexican, and Italian, dips and sauces, soups, and salads. They like recipes that are easy to read and simple to prepare. <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1>Why is the program aimed at 9 to 11 years old? <BR>
</B></font>

This is a transitional age. Control of the child's diet is shifting from total responsibility of the parent to shared responsibility with the child. Children are becoming more autonomous, and they are very impressionable. Health beliefs begin to solidify. Interest in nutrition is still high. The child is not yet buying much of his own food. Dietary quality may not yet have begun to decline.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1><TR><TD WIDTH=590><BR>

<P>
<CENTER><B>5 Easy Ways to Help Kids Eat</B></CENTER>

<CENTER><B>More Fruits and Vegetables</B></CENTER>

<CENTER><B>5 A DAY Tips for Parents<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<hr>
<P>
<ul>
<li><B> Teach kids to eat 5 or more servings of fruits and vegetables every day. Kids who think they need 5 servings for good health eat more. <BR>
</B>
<P>

<li><B> Serve fruits and vegetables at children's parties and celebrations<BR>
</B>
<P>
<li><B> Have your kids help fix vegetables or salads for dinner</B>
<P>
<li><B> Take an interest in what your kids are learning at school about fruits and vegetables<BR>
</B>
<P>
<li><B> Start a garden. Kids who have worked in a garden tend to eat more fruits and vegetables<BR>
</B>
</ul>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Source: California Department of Health Services</TD></TR></FONT></B> </TABLE>
<P><br><p>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=7>EDUCATIONAL RESOURCES<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<img src="../images/5-a-daylogosm.jpg"><u><B><FONT SIZE=6>5 A DAY POWER PLAY!</FONT></B></U>
<P>
The California Department of Health Services has put together a &quot;5 A DAY Power Play, Community Youth Organization: Idea and Resource Kit&quot;. The kit includes 10 fun and easy fruit and vegetable activities to help kids learn to eat 5 servings of fruit and vegetables every day for better health, in both English and Spanish. They also conducted a study to evaluate the activities in the school channel. They saw a 14% increase in fruit and vegetable intake with the children who had School and Community intervention compared to a 7% increase with just school-only intervention. <BR>

<P>
Some of the activities included are 5 A DAY Power Bingo, Power Mysteries, Fruit and Vegetable Scramblers, 5 Senses for 5 A DAY, Secret Snack Pals, Power Passport, Grow a Mini Vegetable Garden, Market Sleuth, Adopt a Community, and Rap It 5 A DAY. Following is a sample activity of the Fruit and Vegetable Scramblers. They also have developed a recipe book designed just for kids.<BR>

<P>
To order please call or write to: <br>
<blockquote>
<B>California Children's 5 a Day Campaign</B>
<br>
<B>Nutrition and Cancer Prevention Program</B>
<br>
<B>California Department of Health Services</B>
<br>
<B>601 North 7th Street</B>
<br>
<B>Sacramento, CA 95814 </B>
<br>
<B>1-800-4-Cancer<BR>
</B></blockquote>
<P><br>
<img src="../images/5-a-dayhealthsm.jpg"><u><B><FONT SIZE=6>5 A DAY BINGO</FONT></B></u>
<P>
Food Services of America and the Montana Department of Public Health and Human Services in conjunction with the EAT RIGHT MONTANA COALITION has a <B>5 A</B> <B>DAY BINGO</B> game that can be used in schools, child care centers, senior meal sites and long- term care. The game is packaged in an attractive binder and comes complete with everything you need to play, including:
<P>
<li> 52 clever <B>CLUE CARDS</B> for produce items from acorn squash to zucchini
<P>
<li> 25 reproducible <B>BINGO CARDS</B> on heavy-duty cardstock
<P>
<li> complete <B>INSTRUCTIONS</B> for using the game in all of the centers listed above
<p>

For more information please call:<BR>

<P>
<blockquote>
<B>Linda Crisp, RD: (406) 238-7854</B>
<P>
<B>internet: linda_crisp@fsafood.com </B>
<BR>
<B>Kathy Andersen, MS, RD: (406) 444-2672</B>
<P>
<B>internet: ande102w@wonder.em.cdc.gov</B>
<BR>
<B>Dayle Hayes, MS, RD: EatRightMT@aol.com</B>

</blockquote>
<P>
To Order Your Copy Today: please send $25.00 plus $5.00 S/H to: <BR>
<blockquote>
<P>
<B>Food Services of America</B>
<BR>
<B>P.O. Box 20997</B>
<BR>
<B>Billings, MT 59104-0997</B>
<BR>
<B>1-800-829-4045<BR></B>
</blockquote>
<p>

</blockquote>
</CENTER>
<P>
<a href="../images/bigpyramid.jpg"><img src="../images/FOODPYRAMIDsm.jpg" border=0></a>  <B><FONT SIZE=4><u>Teach Kids About the <a href="../images/bigpyramid.jpg">FOOD GUIDE PYRAMID!</a></u></FONT></B>
<br>
The USDA created the Food Guide Pyramid as an adaptation from the basic four food groups. It has the base of a healthy diet at the bottom of the pyramid--Whole Grain Bread, Cereal, Rice, and Pasta: 6-11 servings. Remember that a serving is a half a cup of rice, a slice of bread, or a half a bagel. As the pyramid increases it visually relates the need for eating less of the food in the those categories. It is colorful and extremely easy to understand. <BR>
<P>

Print out a copy of the Food Guide Pyramid and have your children color it. Then hang it on your refrigerator, as a reminder for the entire family. Quiz your children, or class, about what was included in their breakfast, lunch, dinner, etcetera. Try to make meal time an educational time. <I>SHAPE </I>magazine reported that mealtime chats boost kids' vocabularies. It stated that, &quot;3 to 4 year-olds whose parents talk to them at dinner time and expose them to &quot;rare&quot; words--- terms such as gymnastics, amusement park and asparagus, for example---score higher on the Peabody Picture Vocabulary Test at age five than children who don't get that stimulation.&quot;<BR>
<P>

Also, with all of the emphasis on eating healthy, don't forget to stress the importance of exercise and active living. When weather permits, go on a walk after dinner with the family instead of sitting down to watch television. Please also remember the importance of water as a key component to the Food Guide Pyramid. Drink a minimum of 8-10 one cup servings every day. For more fitness ideas, link to the fitness section of the site.<BR>
<P>

<BR>
</B>
<P>
<img src="../images/HEARTPOWER.jpg">  <B><FONT SIZE=5><u>HEARTPOWER!</u> American Heart Association</FONT></B>
<p>

The American Heart Association is beginning their new Heart Power Campaign<B><FONT SIZE=5> </FONT></B>in the Fall of 1996. HEARTPOWER! is a preschool through middle school program that includes a rich collection of materials -- each component is easy to integrate into day-to-day instruction. Every level of HEARTPOWER! is packed with fun, motivating activities to teach about nutrition, physical activity, how the heart works, and living tobacco-free. <BR>

<P>
The American Heart Association also has other programs designed to help us keep our hearts healthy from preschool to adulthood. Some of the activities include: Heart Partners, Hoops for Heart, Jump Rope for Heart, Hearty School Lunch, Heart at Work, American Heart Walk, and American Heart Month (February). <BR>

<P>
For details, call <B><FONT SIZE=5>1-800-AHA-USA1</FONT></B>. <BR>
<BR>
<br>
<P>
<img src="../images/HIGHFIVE.jpg" border=0>  <B><FONT SIZE=5><u>&quot;Natural High-Five&quot;:</u> Nutrition Calendar</FONT></B>
<br>
Manning Enterprises has created a Natural High-Five Calendar, a spin-off from &quot;Vinnie's Fruit and Veggie Friends&quot;, an educational play designed for children's theater. It's a story about a little boy who sees himself inadequate and undermines his ability to grow a backyard garden. One by one the characters, which are different vegetables and fruits, come alive to teach Vinnie how to build his self-esteem and become the person he dreams of being. In doing this, the characters also teach him about proper nutrition.<BR>
<p>

The calendar, which features the fruit and vegetable characters, is designed for children and their parents to work together at home, to reinforce the nutrition education the children have learned. The calendar is very interactive with a vibrant color scheme on each of the monthly sheets where you write in the dates. When they fulfill their Natural High-Five recommendations, they place a sticker that day. The calendar also has an outline of a hand print, listing the nutrient recommendations, where the child can give the calendar a &quot;high-five&quot;. Each of the monthly sheets are bordered with the fruit and veggie characters, types of grains, and milk. These are provided in black outline so the child can color his/her differently each month. The stickers provided for the calendar also coincide with the months, for example, July has flags and November has turkeys.<BR>

<P>
There is also a nutrition review sheet of major vitamins and minerals to help parents answer children's questions and a coloring book, posters, and a home video of the play coming soon! The calendar's name also enforces an underlying message to say no to drugs, yes to good nutrition! <BR>

<P>
<CENTER>To order please call, fax, or write to:<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>
<blockquote>
<B>Manning Enterprises</B></CENTER>

<CENTER><B>Educational Entertainment</B></CENTER>

