<TITLE>MANN'S HEALTH AND FITNESS REPORT</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<body text="#001831" link="#001831" vlink="#001831" background="../images/smallicons/Icon_umbckgrd.gif">
<p><br>
<center>
<table cellpadding="12" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600">
<tr>
<td>


<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>MANN'S HEALTH AND FITNESS REPORT<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Fitness</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=4> is defined by
the <U>Oxford American Dictionary</U> as &quot;in good athletic
condition or health.&quot; Of course fitness can mean a lot of
different things and cover a wide variety of activities. Fitness
helps you take care of your body by keeping it strong, resistant
to disease, and full of energy. What is your fitness level? Do
you have any specific fitness goals? Below are some Fitness Facts
that you may find surprising. If you do, please read ahead, and
hopefully we can answer some questions you have about becoming
physically fit and healthy. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<img src="../images/bullets/redline.jpg">

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>FITNESS FACTS<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P><b>
&quot; Nearly one in four adults in the U.S. spends his or her
leisure time sitting around doing little or nothing at all physical,
according to the <I>Archives of Internal Medicine</I>.&quot; 
<BR>

<P>
&quot;Walking just 30 to 45 minutes a day, three times a week
-- or participating in an activity that expends a similar amount
of energy -- can cut a post-menopausal woman's risk of heart attack
in half, reports the <I>Archives of Internal Medicine</I>.&quot;
<BR>

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<I>SHAPE</I>, June 1996<BR>

<P>
&quot; Seven out of 10 American adults participated in at least
one outdoor activity in 1994, according to the American Recreation
Coalition. Though &quot;pleasure driving&quot; held the number-one
ranking, we like to think respondents were on their way to swimming,
fishing and cycling (numbers 2, 3, and 5).&quot;<BR>

<P>
&quot; While a third of the country is now overweight, a new government
report states that more than 40 percent of all women believe they're
overweight, but in fact are not.&quot; <BR>

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<I>SELF</I>, June 1996<BR>

<P>
&quot;According to current guidelines issued by the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention and the American College of Sports
Medicine, people can reap significant health benefits simply by
tallying up a daily half-hour of moderate activity -- say, gardening,
walking to work, or taking the stairs instead of the elevator.&quot;
<BR>

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<I>SHAPE</I>, April 1995<BR>

<P>
&quot; Less than ten percent of Americans exercise three or more
times a week at the level necessary to improve aerobic fitness.&quot;
<BR>

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<I>Good Housekeeping</I>, October 1993<BR>

<P>
&quot; Exercising while you're eating healthy may not only help
you lose weight faster and boost your mood, it may also help you
stick to your healthy eating program.&quot;<BR>

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<I>SHAPE</I>, January 1996 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<img src="../images/bullets/redline.jpg">

<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=12 bgcolor=silver>
<tr>
<td><b>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>BEING ACTIVE VS. WORKING OUT<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Americans have an obsession with work. If they aren't going to
work, they are working out, and even when studying, we're doing
homework. The problems that we've pointed out in the Fitness Facts
about American inactivity is that people look at activity as <U>work</U>.
We need to change our attitudes towards working out and look at
being active. Living an active lifestyle may include working out
at a gym, but more importantly, it means just getting out of the
house and moving. Some tips for improving your activity are:<BR>
<ul>
<P>
<li> Turn up the stereo and dance. Grab your spouse or children and
just get moving to your favorite tunes.<BR>

<P>
<li> Park your car at the back of the parking lot; the extra walk
will take as long as it would to circle to find a closer parking
space. <BR>

<P>
<li> Take your dog or children (or a neighbor's dog) on a walk. If
it's cold or rainy, bundle up and grab an umbrella. <BR>

<P>
<li> Go outside and do some yard work: plant a garden, rake leaves,
shovel snow, pull weeds, or clean out your garage or shed.<BR>

<P>
<li> Always take the stairs when you have a chance. Walking up and
down stairs is great exercise.<BR>
</ul><blockquote>
<P><blockquote>
Source: Reach For It!<br> Canadian Produce Marketing Association<BR>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Self Esteem and Body Image</FONT></B>
<br>
There is a growing concern with body image and self esteem. With
one third of Americans being overweight and the government report
saying that 40% of women say they are overweight when in fact
they are not, has to do with unrealistic body images. Fashion
magazines are covered front to back with the so-called &quot;ideal&quot;
woman. These women models are genetically different from average
women. Why do you think there are less than a dozen Supermodels
in the world? <BR>

<P>
The ideal height for a model is 5'9&quot;(175 cm), when in fact
the average women is between 5'3&quot; and 5'4&quot; (163 cm)
. On the average a model's weight is about ten pounds under the
healthy recommended weight for her height. The average model at
a height of 5'9&quot; weighs 123 pounds (55 kg), when the upper
end of the recommended weight chart is 170 pounds (76.5 kg). The
women of average height , 5'4&quot;, weighs about 142 pounds (64
kg). Models even lack the adequate amount of body fat (17%) needed
for menstruation and childbearing. Even their hip measurements
of 34 to 35 inches are very rare in reality, but are an industry
standard. What women need to remember is that a model's body is
her profession.<BR>

<P>
Remember, how we feel about ourselves is how people will perceive
us. Having a positive attitude about yourself is the best way
to feel good about yourself. Better yet, it helps reflect your
positive attitude upon others. Laughing and smiling burns calories.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<img src="../images/bullets/redline.jpg">


<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Why should we exercise?<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
Exercise, defined by the <U>Oxford American Dictionary</U>, means
an &quot;activity requiring physical exertion, done for the sake
of health.&quot; There are two different types of exercise you
can engage in: aerobic and anaerobic. Aerobic exercise means that
you are using oxygen. It usually is a sustained use of large muscle
groups for a duration. This duration allows the body to respond
to the increased need for oxygen the muscles that are working
require. Some believe that our bodies don't &quot;burn fat&quot;
until 20 minutes into our workout, but this is false. Our bodies
burn calories at rest, therefore any increase in activity will
burn additional calories, thus initiating a reduction in fat.
<BR>

<P>
Anaerobic exercise is defined as short burst of energy that does
not use oxygen and lasts 10 to 30 seconds. For the first 2 to
3 minutes of a workout our bodies are using the limited amount
of glycogen (sugar in the muscle) at the site of the muscle. Any
activity past that is aerobic activity, but each person differs
with there anaerobic/aerobic threshold. Meaning that someone may
take 2 to 3 minutes to reach aerobic exercise, while another may
take ten minutes. A person just beginning a workout program is
a good example of this.<BR>

<P>
Exercise is not just for you body, but critical for your mind.
Exercise makes you feel energized and puts you in a great mood.
After a great workout sometimes people mention a natural &quot;high&quot;
caused by a release of endorphins in the body. Exercise can be
a special time for yourself or time set aside with a good friend.
Remember to pick out types of exercises that you enjoy and always
vary so you don't get bored.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Strength Training and Endurance Exercises<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
The benefits of strength training are numerous. Building lean
muscle mass helps prevent injuries by adding additional support
for the joints and to promote muscle balance for proper posture.
It also helps increase bone density and strengthens connective
tissues. Strength training helps you perform everyday tasks as
well as improve your sports performance. And best of all, it improves
your appearance and enhancement of lean body mass, which increases
your metabolism. When thinking of lean body mass, remember the
saying, &quot;use it or lose it,&quot; because if you stop working
your muscles, they will soon disappear. That's why it is so important
to do light strength training, as a minimum, especially for the
elderly. Read books on strength training (local library), rent
videos, or ask a certified personal trainer (at most gyms - check
for certification). <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Starting an Exercise Program<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>When starting an exercise program please consult
your physician to make sure you are in good health. Ease into
a program instead of jumping full force, especially if you were
inactive before. This will allow your body to adapt slowly and
will lessen the chances of becoming really sore, discouraged,
and quitting. The following are various activities and the estimated
energy expenditure per hour.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><center>
<img src="../images/nutrition-chart.jpg">
<P></center>

<P>
Source: <U>Nutrition &amp; Diet Therapy</U>, by Sue Rodwell Williams
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Determine Your Fitness Goals </FONT></B>
<P>
Some examples of fitness goals are: increase your physical activity;
lose some excess body fat; try to eat more healthy; or increase
your muscle mass. Once you determine them, be sure to make your
fitness goals realistic. They will be easier to stick with and
to get started. Below are some tips for beginning and maintaining
an active, healthy lifestyle. <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=12 bgcolor=silver>
<tr>
<td><b>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Healthy Lifestyle Tips<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P><ul>
<li> Develop an exercise routine that easily fits your schedule.
It's easier to stick with.<BR>

<P>
<li> Don't diet. Make healthy dietary changes that are realistic.
An example is to not stop eating sandwiches, but say no to mayonnaise
and cheese and get lean turkey for your meat. <BR>

<P>
<li> Don't go to bed after a large meal. Either try and eat earlier
or go on a walk after dinner instead of hitting the couch.<BR>

<P>
<li> Consider exercise as an appointment with yourself. Treat it
like you would a meeting or lunch date.<BR>

<P>
<li> Find any form of exercise you enjoy, and do a variety of activities
regularly.<BR>

<P>
<li> Get a partner: a friend, spouse, child, or pet. It will keep
you both going.<BR>

<P>
<li> Take pictures to see results of your efforts and keep old ones
around for encouragement.<BR>

<P>
<li> Eat five to six small healthful meals a day to keep your metabolism
(starving shuts it off) running and to prevent you from ever getting
really hungry.<BR>

<P>
<li> Don't forbid anything. Allow yourself treats in moderation.
<BR>

<P>
<li> Listen to your body: if it hurts, stop; if it's hungry, eat.
<BR>

<P>
<li> Drink lots and lots of water. At least 64 ounces a day (2 large
water bottles); more on days you exercise intensely or when it's
especially hot. <BR>

<P>
<li> Take days off from exercise. Your body needs time to build and
repair.<BR>

<P>
<li> Make sure you are making these lifestyle changes for yourself
and no one else.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P><img src="../images/FOODPYRAMIDsm.jpg">
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Healthy Eating Tips <BR>
</FONT></B>
<P><ul>
<li> Follow the USDA's Food Guide Pyramid. Emphasize the bulk of
your food sources from fruit and vegetables, then carbohydrates,
dairy and protein.<BR>

<P>
<li> Remember what a proper portion size is. The Food Guide Pyramid
recommends 6 to 11 servings of grain products, but a serving size
is half a bagel, half a cup of rice or pasta, or one slice of
bread. A lot of people see weight gain due to excessive intake
of carbohydrates, so, stick to whole grains and cereals, stay
away from refined bread, cereal, and rice, and remember serving
sizes.<BR>

<P>
<li> Try to eat a large breakfast and lunch with snacks in between
and less at dinner. Also, try and eat a more vegetable based dinner.
For example, focus your meal on a baked potato instead of steak
or chicken.<BR>

<P>
<li> Eat more servings of calcium rich foods like low-fat dairy products
or broccoli, and eat less protein, especially if you are a woman.
<BR>

<P>
<li> Remember to consume water. At least 64 ounces per day. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>


</ul>
<img src="../images/bullets/redline.jpg">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>How Many Calories Do You Need?<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The following steps are tool to help figure out your daily caloric needs. Remember that this is just a guideline for you to follow and if you have any questions, please contact your doctor or a local registered dietitian.<BR>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Step One:</FONT> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Multiply your ideal body weight or present weight by 10 (use your ideal body weight if you want to lose body fat). How to find your ideal body weight is given below. <BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>EXAMPLE: <BR>
145 (Present or ideal body weight)<BR>
<U>X10<BR>
</U>1450 (kcal you need daily to rest)<BR>
</FONT>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Step Two: </FONT>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Find your activity factor in the list below and multiply it by your weight to get the calories you need to perform daily activities. <BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>EXAMPLE:<BR>
145 <BR>
<U>X 5</U> (activity factor) <BR>
725 (kcal you need for daily ativities) <BR>
</FONT>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Step Three: </FONT>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Add the sums from steps one and two to get the calories you need daily to maintain your present weight. <BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>EXAMPLE: <BR>
1450 <BR>
<U>+ 725</U> <BR>
2175 (kcal you need daily to maintain your present/ideal weight)<BR>
</FONT>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Step Four:</FONT> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
If you want ot lose weight, subtract 250-500 calories a day and increase your exercise to burn an additional 250-500 kcal/day. This will allow a healthy weight loss of 1 to 2 pounds per week. To gain weight add an additional 500 kcal/day and increase your strength training to ensure a weight gain of helathy muscle and not fat.<BR>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=4>EXAMPLE: <BR>
2175 <BR>
<U>- 500</U> (dietary kcal to eliminate) <BR>
1675 (daily kcal intake to lose weight)</FONT>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<table border=1 cellpadding=12 bgcolor=silver>
<tr>
<td><b>
<FONT SIZE=4>Ideal Body Weight Estimation:<BR>
</FONT>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<U><FONT SIZE=4>female:</FONT></U> 100 lb for first five feet, 5 lb for each additional inch (+/- 15 lb)<BR>
<BR>
<U><FONT SIZE=4>male</FONT></U><FONT SIZE=4>: </FONT>105 lb for first five feet, 6 lb for each additional inch (+/- 15 lb)<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</td>
</tr>
</table>


<P><table border=1 cellpadding=12 bgcolor=silver>
<tr>
<td><b>
<FONT SIZE=4>Activity Factors:<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=5>3 </FONT>Sedentary: no exercise<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>4 </FONT>Moderately Active: Exercises, gardens, does housework 3 - 5 times per week for 20 to 30 minutes at a time. Uses stairs and walks briskly.<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>5</FONT> Active: Exercises 3 - 5 times a week for 60 minutes at a time. Uses stairs and walks briskly.<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=5>7 </FONT>Very Active: Exercise 3 - 5 times a week for 90-plus minutes at a time. Uses stairs and walks briskly. Daily physical activity and competitve with recreational sports. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
REMEMBER: These are only estimates. Individual activity factors and body frames vary from person to person and the individual's lean body mass. The most important thing to remember in reaching and maintaining a healthy lifestyle is to get to know your body and your body type. Every person who is 5'4&quot;, is not going to weigh 120 lb. The average person's body is on the upper end of the scale, around 135lb. So please, remember to personalize your needs based on the guidelines given.

<p>
<img src="../images/bullets/redline.jpg">
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>The Importance of Water</FONT></B>
<P>
The human body can only live a few days without water. Although
not classified as a nutrient, water is the single most important
factor to human life. More than half the body's weight is water
and it is the basis of all bodily fluids and most functions. Water
is the single most important factor in losing and maintaining
your weight. It helps the body feel full, while also suppressing
the appetite and helping the body metabolize stored fat. It helps
treat fluid retention, which is caused by too little water or
excess sodium. Water maintains muscle tone by giving muscles their
natural ability to contract and prevents dehydration during exercise.
<BR>

<P>
It is recommended to drink at least 64 ounces each day. That is
actually the minimum recommendation. During exercise of even mild
intensity, your body requires more water (2 cups every 15 minutes).
Cold water is absorbed more quickly than warmer temperatures and
some people believe it helps you body burn extra calories to warm
it up.<p>
<img src="../images/bullets/redline.jpg">

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Healthy Rules to Live By<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P><ul>
<li><B><FONT SIZE=4> </FONT></B>Don't get compulsive about food.
It's meant to be enjoyed.<BR>

<P>
<li> Eat only 30 percent of your calories from fat, 55 percent from
carbohydrate and 15 percent from protein (includes dairy). <BR>

<P>
<li> Eat several small meals a day, instead of three big ones. <BR>

<P>
<li> Drink at least two liters of water per day (64 ounces). <BR>
<BR>
</ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
