<head>
<!-- MANN'S BROCCOLI, FOOD SERVICE, authored by gavdw for fine.com  -->
<!--  Last Edited 7/1/96 by Glenn Van Der Werff  -->
<title>Tom Answers FAQ</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFEBD7">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600" cellpadding="5" border="0">

<tr>
<td>
<h1>Tom Answers:<br>
<nobr><font color="#000080" size="+2">F</font><font size="+1">REQUENTLY </font>
<font color="#000080" size="+2">A</font><font size="+1">SKED </font>
<font color="#000080" size="+2">Q</font><font size="+1">UESTIONS</font></nobr>
</h1>

<font color="green"><i>
Q) What does Broccoli Wokly mean?</font></i><br>
A) Broccoli Wokly is the name of a random-cut broccoli florette introduced by Mann Packing Company in the mid-Eighties. It has a crown width that ranges from 1" to 2 3/4". It was named by David L. Stidolph, the "father of the fresh broccoli florette" and the Director of Foodservice for Mann Packing at the time. Dave was going to do a promotion for the florette with a company that manufactured Woks as he saw the application for the florette being used in stir frys. The promotion never took place, but its safe to say that Broccoli Wokly has higher name recognition than any broccoli product on the market.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<a href="../images/footers/footer.map">
<IMG SRC="../images/footers/foodbutt.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
