<html>

<head>
<!-- MANN'S BROCCOLI, FOOD SERVICE, authored by gavdw for fine.com  -->
<!--  Last Edited 7/1/96 by Glenn Van Der Werff  -->
<title>Tom Answers FAQ</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFEBD7">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#ffffff" width="600" cellpadding="12" border="0">

<tr>
<td>
<font size="7" color="#001831" face="Helvetica">Letters to Tom</font>
<p>
<font color="green"><i>
  How long do you steam broccoli so that it is cooked, yet vitamins and minerals are retained?</i></font><br>
                            -Bryan, The Dolantos, Seattle, WA<p>

The best routes toward preserving the nutrients in fresh broccoli- and other vegetables- is to combine the least amount of water with the shortest cooking time.
<p>
<font color="green"><i>
What is the best method for cleaning broccoli?</i></font><br>
-Liz Nedeff, the Acorn Cafe, Austin, TX
<p>
Broccoli can be washed.  However, don't soak fresh broccoli if you hope to benefit from the B and C vitamins broccoli contains.
<p>
<font color="green"><i>
 Is it true that copper cooking pots can destroy certain vitamins in broccoli?</i></font><br>

Yes, 
Believe it or not, cooking pots lined with copper can destroy vitamin C, folic acid and even vitamin E.  Aluminum, stainless steel, enamel and glass are better utensils for cooking fresh broccoli and retaining nutrients.

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>
