<title>Mann's Broccoli Recipes</title>
<!--  created by gvdw on 7/26/96 for Mann's Broccoli  -->
<!--  last edited on 8/19/96 by gavdw  -->
</head>


<!-----------------------------Keywords------------------------->

<!--

Unbelievable Broccoli 
Mealtime Snack Appetizer Lunch Dinner 
Region Buffalo New York 
Kids
Entertaining Pot luck dinners 
Product Mann's Broccoli Wokly 

-->

<!---------------------------End Keywords----------------------->



<body text="#000000" link="green" vlink="#6A006A" bgcolor="#FFEBD7"><center>
<a name=top>
<!-------------------------------Add Below Here--------------------------->
 


<table width="600" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" border="1" bordercolordark="#FFEBD7" bordercolorlight="#808040" cellpadding="7">
  <tr>
  <td><font face="Helvetca" size="3">

<font face="Helvetica" color="green"><b>
MANNS SPICY BUFFALO POTATO SKINS</b></font>
<p><font face="Helvetica" color="#6A006A">
Weve combined the best features of two popular appetizers to create this irresistible vegetarian snack.  For convenience, the potatoes can be baked up to 24 hours in advance; simply wrap them in a clean tea towel and refrigerate.  These are so good you may want to double the recipe!
</font><p>

<img src="../../images/foodshots/buffalopotatoskins.jpg" align=right>
<font face="Helvetica">
3 large russet potatoes (about 1 1/2 pounds total), baked until tender
3 Tablespoons melted butter<br>
4 teaspoons hot pepper sauce, such as Franks Louisiana Red Hot Sauce, 	or more to taste<br>
1 1/2 cups <b>Manns  Broccoli Wokly Florettes</b>, cut in half lengthwise.<br>
6 Tablespoons blue cheese salad dressing, purchased or homemade
<p>
1.Preheat oven to 375.  When potatoes are cool enough to handle, cut each in half  lengthwise. Scoop out center flesh from the potato halves, leaving a shell about 1/4-inch thick. Arrange the potato skins cut-side up on a baking sheet. 
<p>
2.In a medium bowl, mix melted butter with hot sauce until well blended.  Stir in the broccoli, tossing to coat with the butter mixture. 
<p>
3.Divide broccoli mixture evenly among potato skins, mounding if necessary.  Use the remaining butter in the bowl to drizzle over the filled potato skins.
<p>
4.Bake uncovered until the potato skins are nicely browned and the broccoli is crisp-tender, 12 to 15 minutes.  Just before serving, drizzle 1 Tablespoon of blue cheese dressing over each potato.  Serve warm. 
<p>
Serves 3 to 6 


<p>
<u><b>Nutrients Per Serving:</b></font></u>
<pre>
Calories:	240	Vitamin A:	106 IU
Protein:	4 G	Vitamin C:	37 mg
Carbohydrates:	29 G	Thiamin:	0.1 mg
Dietary Fiber:	4.7 G	Riboflavin: 	0.1 mg
Fat-total:	13.1 G	Niacin:	        2 mg
Saturated fat	4.9 G	Calcium:	46 mg
Cholesterol:	23.2 mg	Iron:	        4 mg
Sodium:	        244 mg	Cal. from Fat:	47 %
</pre>
  </td>
  </tr>
  </table>
<!--------------------------Add Above Here------------------------->
<a href="../mkrecipestoc.htm">
Back to Mom's Favorite Recipes</a>
<p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>
