<A NAME="New test offers diagnosis of CJD"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">New test offers diagnosis of CJD</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">by Jeremy Laurance<BR>
<BR>
The Times ... January 10 1997<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>Scientists believe they have found a <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">simple
test to give early diagnosis of the new strain of</FONT></B> <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Creutzfeldt-Jakob
disease</FONT></B>, which is linked to eating beef. At present, <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B>
can be diagnosed with certainty only after death.<BR>
<BR>
The discovery will show whether the disease is spreading and which patients
with early signs of dementia would respond to treatment. <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">The
test involves removing a piece of tissue from the tonsils</FONT></B>, possible
under local anaesthetic.<BR>
<BR>
John Collinge and his colleagues at Imperial College and St Mary's Hospital,
London, report in The Lancet that they have found a prion protein characteristic
of the new strain of <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B> in a tonsil
sample taken from a woman who had died of the disease. The prion protein
was discovered by the same team last October in the brains of people who
had died with the disease. The new variant of <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B>
is different from other versions but virtually identical to BSE , or &quot;<B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">mad
cow</FONT></B>&quot; disease.<BR>
<BR>
Although there is currently no treatment for <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B>
, confirming the diagnosis is important because in its early stages the
symptoms are similar to other degenerative diseases which are treatable.
Diagnosis is at present only possible by brain biopsy, a dangerous and
unreliable operation.<BR>
<BR>
Professor Collinge said it was too soon to predict how many cases of the
new strain there would be, but that <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">if an epidemic
ensued, a simple test would be essential</FONT></B>.<BR>
<!*************** NEW ARTICLE STARTS HERE ***************>
