<A NAME="E coli found in lamb for the first time"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">E coli found in lamb for the first
time</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">By Celia Hall, Medical Editor<BR>
<BR>
Daily Telegraph ... Friday 3 January 1997<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>The food poisoning bacterium <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">E coli</FONT></B>,
responsible for 16 deaths in Scotland, has been <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">found
in lamb</FONT></B> for the first time, the consumers' magazine Which? says
today.<BR>
<BR>
The Public Health Laboratory Service confirmed yesterday that its Sheffield
laboratory had found the bacterium in two tests, one of carcases and one
of lamb products. The organism is more usually associated with beef.<BR>
<BR>
The Which? report says: &quot;The PHLS scientists inspected 700 sheep carcases
slaughtered for human consumption and found the bacteria in 18 (2.6 per
cent) of them. This <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">rate is lower than that of
beef</FONT></B> - one study found E coli 0157 in 22 per cent of raw beef
- but it is still of concern.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The laboratory said that a follow-up study also found E coli in lamb products
and both of the studies were published in the Veterinary Record. &quot;Our
advice remains the same,&quot; a spokesman said. &quot;The bacteria is
killed by normal cooking. People should make sure that they cook meat properly.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Which? says all lamb, and minced lamb in particular, must be cooked through
until the juices run clear.<BR>
<BR>
It says the number of reported cases of E coli food poisoning &quot;has
been rising steadily over the past few years, reaching more than 1,000
in 1995&quot;.<BR>
<!*************** NEW ARTICLE STARTS HERE ***************>
