<A NAME="Call for watchdog as CJD toll hits 15"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Call for watchdog as CJD toll hits
15</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">by Michael Hornsby, Agriculture Correspondent<BR>
<BR>
The Times ... January 07 1997<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>Paddy Ashdown called last night for the <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">creation
of an independent body to monitor food safety</FONT></B> and dispel a &quot;<B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">climate
of fear</FONT></B>&quot; among consumers after the beef crisis. <BR>
<BR>
The call by the Liberal Democrat leader came as the Department of Health
confirmed that <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">15 people were so far believed
to have fallen victim</FONT></B> to a strain of <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">Creutzfeldt-Jakob
disease</FONT></B> linked to eating BSE-infected beef . The latest is thought
to have been Victoria Lowther, 19, a hotelier's daughter from Carlisle,
who died in November.<BR>
<BR>
Mr Ashdown accused the Government of <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">relying too
much for scientific guidance on advisers with commercial links</FONT></B>,
and of <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">failing to take prompt precautionary action
against risks to health</FONT></B> and the environment. He told a dinner
at the annual Oxford Farming Conference: &quot;What we need is a stand-alone,
independent commission which, like the Audit Commission, reports to Parliament,
not ministers, and is strong enough to fight its corner in the marketplace.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Citing the recent arrival in supermarkets of products with genetically
engineered soya, but with no mention of that on their labels, Mr Ashdown
said consumers, like farmers, were being left powerless amd bewildered.<BR>
<BR>
Labour has said it will set up an independent food body if it wins power.<BR>
<BR>
The Department of Health would not confirm that the <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">fifteenth
</FONT><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B> <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">case
</FONT></B>was Miss Lowther, although reports last month suggested her
death was caused by the strain, which hits the young.<BR>
<BR>
The latest monthly figures show the number of referrals to the national
<B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B> surveillance centre in Edinburgh
in 1996 was <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">111</FONT></B> to the end of November,
the highest since 1990. On past experience, <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">half
</FONT></B>will turn out to be genuine <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B>
cases, mostly of the &quot;sporadic&quot; form, which affects mainly older
people and is not linked with beef.<BR>
<BR>
* Almost &pound;1 million will be available in 1997-98 to help farmers
convert to organic methods. The Ministry of Agriculture said that even
the modest amount of aid has not been fully taken up since the scheme was
launched in 1994.<BR>
