<HR>
<A NAME="Paris bans Swiss cattle after BSE border blockade"></A><BR>
<H3><CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Paris bans Swiss cattle after BSE border blockade</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<FONT COLOR="009F00">from Adam Sage in Paris and Peter Capella in Geneva<BR>
Times    ...   December 21 1996</FONT><BR><BR>
The French Government yesterday bowed to pressure from its cattle farmers and extended its ban on beef imports to Switzerland, the country worst affected by &quot;<STRONG>mad cow</STRONG></FONT>&quot; disease after Britain.<BR><BR>
Farmers in eastern France have been pressing for such a ban, with some mounting a blockade of the border, on the ground that Swiss cattle could infect their herds and that importation of beef from the country was undermining consumer confidence. Austria, Germany and Italy have already taken measures to ban cattle from Switzerland.<BR><BR>
Yesterday, Philippe Vasseur, the French Agriculture Minister, said Paris would ask the European Union to establish a common policy on Swiss beef, as it has with Britain.<BR><BR>
&quot;This precautionary measure is taken pending the official position of the European Union. It is justified by the absolute priority we place on protecting consumers,&quot; M Vasseur said.<BR><BR>
Switzerland has reported 230 cases of BSE and Britain 160,000. The Swiss authorities say they will eradicate the disease through a SFr6.5 million (2.9 million) programme to slaughter at least 1,500 cows. But the programme was not enough to stem anger in France, where cattle farmers' earnings have fallen sharply this year.<BR><BR>
Paris at first tried to resist farmers' pressure, arguing that a nationwide ban was unnecessary. However, local authorities near the Swiss border paved the way for a government climb-down when they banned Swiss beef from the Doubs department in October.<BR><BR>
Yesterday M Vasseur said some Swiss beef products could enter France under &quot;exceptional circumstances&quot; and tight sanitary conditions. But he said there would be no exceptions to the ban on Swiss cattle.<BR><BR>
Despite the ban, French farmers at the Swiss border said that they would not stop their blockade of lorries carrying cattle. They have forced several such vehicles to turn back to Switzerland since Wednesday.<BR><BR>
An official at the Swiss veterinary office said the French decision appeared to be motivated more by commercial and political criteria than by health matters. Last month 652 head of cattle were exported to France, as opposed to 28 between January and August.<BR><BR>
The Swiss Farm Producers Association accused the French of &quot;verging on hypocrisy&quot;. It claimed that French companies fraudulently relabelled contaminated British cattle feed and re-exported it to Switzerland before 1989, and that Paris had not taken action against them.<BR><BR>
Austria, Germany and Italy banned Swiss beef imports several months ago. With 68 outbreaks of BSE in 1995, and 45 so far this year, the epidemic is regarded as declining in Switzerland.
<HR>
<A NAME="EU welcomes cull of 100,000 more cattle"></A><BR>
<H3><CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">EU welcomes cull of 100,000 more cattle</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<FONT COLOR="009F00">News in Brief<BR>
Telegraph    ...   December 18 1996</FONT><BR><BR>
European Union farm ministers yesterday cautiously welcomed Britain's decision to slaughter 100,000 more cattle but said it could still be a long time before a ban on British beef exports was lifted. Douglas Hogg, the Agriculture Minister, told a farm ministers' meeting in Brussels that Britain would go ahead with a selective cull. He added that Britain would consider extending the cull to cover cattle affected by maternal transmission if this was scientifically justified.<BR><BR>
The ministers rejected by ten votes to five a proposal to ban sheep, goat and cattle offal from the human and animal food chains. The European Commission had claimed that the brains, eyes and spinal cords of cattle, sheep and goats over one year old were made of tissue most likely to be affected by BSE or scrapie. But most ministers said the measure was unnecessary and too expensive.<BR><BR>
 The farm ministers agreed to ban by 2006 the use of cramped crates for rearing calves over two months old and to improve the diet of veal calves, which have been given a milky diet lacking iron in order to produce white meat.

<HR>
<A NAME="Beef ban to stay despite further cull"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Beef ban to stay despite further
cull</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">By George Jones, Jon Hibbs and Robert Shrimsley<BR>

Telegraph ... Tuesday 17 December 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT><B>The early lifting of the world-wide ban
on British beef exports was ruled out</FONT></B> by the Government and
Brussels last night despite the reinstatement of plans for the selective
slaughter of about 100,000 cattle most at risk of <B>mad
cow</FONT></B> disease. Douglas Hogg, the Agriculture Minister, told MPs
that the removal of the ban was still a &quot;long way off&quot; and refused
to forecast when exports might be resumed.<BR>
<BR>
Franz Fischler, the EU commissioner for agriculture, emphasised that <B>Britain
had still to honour the conditions agreed at the EU summit in Florence
last June</FONT></B>. Other EU farm ministers made clear that they were
adopting a &quot;wait and see&quot; approach to the British proposals.<BR>
<BR>
Mr Hogg angered Tory Euro-sceptics in the Commons by admitting that there
was no scientific justification for the new cull, which will cost &pound;90
million on top of the &pound;3.2 billion the Government has already earmarked
for dealing with the crisis. He accepted that it was <B>the
political price Britain would have to pay for seeking progress towards
lifting the ban some time next year</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Tory MPs branded the move as &quot;appeasement&quot; of Brussels and expressed
dismay that Britain had received no firm guarantees from the European Commission
about the resumption of exports. The ban was imposed nine months ago after
the Government admitted a possible link between BSE and the human form
of the disease, <B>Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease</FONT></B>
(<B>CJD</FONT></B>).<BR>
<BR>
Tony Blair, the Labour leader, accused the Government of <B>&quot;serial
incompetence&quot;</FONT></B> in the handling of the crisis. He said it
had not made a single piece of progress in having the ban lifted.<BR>
<BR>
On a day dominated by Europe, John Major surprised MPs by declaring that
Britain's relationship with the EU could be determined by decisions taken
over the next 18 months. Downing Street later denied that the Prime Minister
was threatening possible withdrawal, but was hinting at a more arm's-length
relationship with Europe if it developed into an &quot;embryonic superstate&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
Mr Major said that those who talked of Britain pulling out of Europe were
&quot;peddling a delusion&quot; and emphasised that he wanted more than
a trading relationship with Europe. But he made clear that the Government
would not be a party to Franco-German plans for an &quot;inner core&quot;
of states, emphasising that Britain would either stand aside or block such
changes if they put the rest of the EU at a disadvantage.<BR>
<BR>
Mr Major said the EU was approaching some historic decisions. &quot;The
choices made will determine not only the success and stability of Europe
as a whole, but Britain's relationship with it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Mr Hogg's statement on the beef ban preceded the annual Commons debate
on European fisheries policy, which was the first test of the Government's
authority since it lost its majority as a result of Labour's victory in
the Barnsley East by-election last week.<BR>
<BR>
Ministers clearly hoped that the announcement of the cull would please
Ulster Unionist MPs, who now hold the balance of power in the Commons.
They have been angered that the Government has not managed to persuade
Brussels to lift the ban on certified grass-fed beef, which would help
Northern Ireland, where there is a low incidence of BSE.<BR>
<BR>
The selective cull was shelved nearly three months ago because of conflicting
scientific advice and opposition from Tory MPs. Mr Hogg insisted that proceeding
with it was an indispensable pre-condition to obtaining any lifting of
the ban.<BR>
<BR>
But he was unable to offer MPs any timetable. He said it would be a <B>&quot;difficult
and slow process&quot; to achieve a complete lifting of the ban</FONT></B>,
but there was a &quot;reasonable chance&quot; of at least a partial relaxation.
Mr Hogg told MPs that more than a million cattle over 30 months old had
been slaughtered.

<HR>
<A NAME="Hogg announces cull of 100,000 cattle as ministers do U-turn on BSE deal"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Hogg announces cull of 100,000 cattle
as ministers do U-turn on BSE deal</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">by Philip Webster and Charles Bremner<BR>
Times ... December 17 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>Hogg: cull is the only way to make progress<BR>
<BR>
Brussels warns of no early end to ban on British beef<BR>
<BR>
Europe told Britain yesterday that the <B>world ban
on British beef would remain indefinitely</FONT></B>, in spite of the Government's
decision to slaughter 100,000 cattle most at risk from &quot;<B>mad
cow</FONT></B>&quot; disease.<BR>
<BR>
Douglas Hogg, the Agriculture Minister, said the Government was going ahead
with the &pound;150 million cull &shy; first mooted in July, then suspended
in September &shy; because it was the only way to make any progress on
lifting the ban. &quot;It is a political fact, not a scientific fact,&quot;
he told MPs. &quot;If we do not commit ourselves to a selective cull, then
we are certain not to see any progress of any kind.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But even before his Commons statement, the European Commission ruled out
any swift lifting of the ban and one senior Conservative believed it could
last for years.<BR>
<BR>
Franz Fischler, the Agriculture Commissioner, made clear that Britain must
go through all the EU's decision-making hurdles before any softening of
the embargo. Mr Hogg, who will meet agriculture ministers in Brussels today,
admitted that Britain would not secure a timetable. He told MPs that they
<B>&quot;should not be under any illusion as to how
quickly a selective cull will lead to a resumption of exports of British
beef&quot;</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Herr Fischler said that he had not been told officially about Britain's
decision to cull an extra 100,000 cattle and it was up to the Government
to put forward a detailed request to start the machinery agreed at the
Florence summit in June. &quot;I don't see any need to depart from what
was agreed upon,&quot; he said. &quot;I think we need to move forward step
by step as agreed.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That means that a British request, probably to ease the ban on grass-fed
herds certified as BSE-free, must pass through various committees including
the Standing Veterinary Committee. At best, that could take weeks.<BR>
<BR>
Euro-sceptics were glum about the announcement, seeing it as another U-turn
in the face of Brussels pressure. John Townend said: &quot;Many of us just
don't trust our European friends and we think they are going to keep this
ban going for year after year.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But Sir David Naish, president of the National Farmers' Union, welcomed
the announcement, while calling for extra financial help for farmers who
would lose a substantial proportion of their herds. &quot;We are not happy
at the idea of many thousands of healthy animals being culled,&quot; he
said. &quot;But we have long accepted that the Florence agreement had to
be honoured by Britain and that this was the only way to start lifting
the export ban.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Government undertook in Florence to slaughter
up to 147,000 cattle identified as being at particular risk of developing
BSE. These were cattle born between 1989 and 1993 and reared on the same
infected feed as animals that have died of BSE</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
In September the Cabinet shelved plans for the cull, citing new scientific
evidence that BSE would die out naturally around 2001 and that the slaughter
would do little if anything to bring this date nearer. The Government has
now been forced to return to much the same plan it rejected only three
months ago. One difference is that only about 100,000 cattle will need
to be culled because about 50,000 of those targeted in June have already
been killed.<BR>
<BR>
The Treasury will pick up &pound;90 million of the compensation bill and
the EU the rest.<BR>

<HR>
<A NAME="Ban on beef 'set to stay until mid-1997'"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Ban on beef 'set to stay until mid-1997'</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">by Patrick Hennessy and Alice Miles<BR>
Evening Standard ... Tuesday, 17 December, 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>Government attempts to persuade Europe to lift the ban on British
beef by slaughtering an extra 110,000 cattle faltered today when EU ministers
warned it could be <B>the middle of next year before
the ban was even relaxed</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg went to battle yet again to get the ban
lifted, telling Brussels: &quot;The ball's in your court.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
He flew in for meetings with fellow ministers in the wake of the Government's
controversial decision to press on with the cull of high-risk cattle.<BR>
<BR>
Irish farm minister Ivan Yates, who chaired today's meeting, warned afterwards,
however, that it could be <B>&quot;mid-year 1997&quot;
</FONT></B>before the ban was relaxed.<BR>
<BR>
He welcomed Britain's decision to undertake the selective cull as &quot;entering
a new phase of this whole process&quot;, adding that a lead could be taken
on lifting the ban in Northern Ireland.<BR>
<BR>
Asked, however, when the first phase of the easing might happen, he told
BBC Radio 4's World At One: &quot;I don't think one can predict with certainty
because we have to await the operation of the cull, decisions by the Commission,
the Standing Veterinary Committee, and subsequently the Council.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;But indicative dates were set forward as a movement on the process
in January/February in relation to reporting back and the particular proposal
on the certified hard scheme being ready in February, and then we're talking
about mid-year before perhaps the full inspection process could be complete
and early decisions could be made round the mid-year of 1997.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Before the meeting, Mr Hogg admitted there was little hope of speedy progress
towards a timetable for lifting the worldwide ban, and that negotiations
would be &quot;difficult&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
He also confessed there was little or no scientific justification for the
new cull, which he said ministers had agreed to simply to persuade the
EU to move forward.<BR>
<BR>
Mr Hogg said: &quot;EU member states are facing a lot of internal pressure
not to lift the ban but we have now put the ball in their court.&quot;
Meanwhile, John Major was expecting a tough Question Time in the Commons
this afternoon with a fresh round of attacks on beef and the Government's
general stance towards Europe.<BR>
<BR>
The Government's victories in two votes on European fishing policy last
night, by wider margins than expected, won it four weeks' breathing space
before MPs end their Christmas break on 13 January.<BR>

Nonetheless, the votes demonstrated how much Mr Major's minority Government
depends on the nine Ulster Unionist MPs, who abstained last night.

<HR>
<A NAME="Sheep with human gene produce first drug batch"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Sheep with human gene produce first
drug batch</FONT></H3><I>[There would be worry here about transfer of scrapie to humans.  Sheep may also have been infected with BSE -- webmaster]</I>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">by Steve Connor, Science Correspondent<BR>
Sunday Times ... December 15<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>Scientists have extracted the first drug to treat human diseases
from the milk of genetically engineered sheep. The breakthrough could result
in scores of new medicines being produced by farmyard animals.<BR>
<BR>
The first clinical trials of the drug, which was drawn from sheep carrying
human genes, began last week. The drug will be used to treat lung infections
caused by cystic fibrosis, the most common lethal genetic disease in Europe.<BR>
<BR>
It represents a turning point for the pharmaceuticals industry, which sees
the technique as a means of producing cheaply a new generation of medicines
which at present are too costly for widespread use.<BR>
<BR>
The process, known as &quot;pharming&quot;, promises to produce copious
quantities of up to 100 other drugs based on vital human proteins that
cannot be easily made by conventional methods.<BR>
<BR>
The breakthrough has been made by scientists at PPL Therapeutics, a small
biotechnology firm near Edinburgh, who injected a human gene into the embryos
of sheep, then bred a flock of 200 genetically engineered animals on their
secure farm near the city.<BR>
<BR>
From their milk, they have extracted a protein called alpha-1 antitrypsin
(AAT), which can be used to inhibit the destruction of lung tissue in cystic
fibrosis patients. Enough medicine can be extracted from the milk of one
sheep to meet the needs of about 15 patients.<BR>
<BR>
Dr Diana Bilton, a consultant physician at Papworth hospital, Cambridge,
who will lead the clinical trials of the drug, said that until now only
small amounts of AAT could be extracted from human blood, which meant it
was costly and ran a slight risk of carrying blood-borne infections.<BR>

Other drugs likely to be produced in animal milk include fibrinogen, or
tissue &quot;glue&quot;, which can be used to form a biodegradable suture
over a wound, a natural antibiotic called lactoferrin, and a range of drugs
involved in promoting or dissolving blood clots.<BR>
<BR>
Genzyme, an American biotechnology company based in Boston, Massachusetts,
is also close to producing a drug from the milk of genetically engineered
goats. The firm plans to use it as an anti-clotting agent in trials on
27 American patients undergoing heart-bypass operations.<BR>
<BR>
The company said that the drug, antithrombin-III, may also alleviate the
symptoms of a wide range of other disorders, including liver disease, septicaemia,
shock, burns and complications caused by organ transplants.<BR>
<BR>
Dr John Clark, one of the original inventors of the technique and a scientist
at the government-funded Roslin Institute, in Edinburgh, said the current
clinical trials vindicated his ideas: &quot;<B>Everybody thought we were mad.</B>
It was a case of 'don't call us, we'll call you'.&quot;
<HR>
<A NAME="Brussels guilty of BSE cover-up"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Brussels guilty of BSE cover-up</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">Peter Conradi, Brussels<BR>

Sunday Times ... December 15<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>The European commission <B>systematically
covered up the danger to human health</FONT></B> posed by &quot;<B>mad
cow</FONT></B>&quot; disease (BSE) over more than four years, an inquiry
by the European parliament has heard.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Its report will accuse the commission of yielding
to British government pressure and effectively putting the interests of
farmers and the beef industry before consumers.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B>Its author claims this amounts to a &quot;<B>consistent
pat tern of cover-up</FONT></B>&quot;, implicating senior European Union
officials up to Ray MacSharry, the former Irish EU farm commissioner.<BR>
<BR>
The report will also <B>criticise the British government</FONT></B>,
which between 1990 and 1994 repeatedly <B>refused
permission</FONT></B> for EU veterinary experts to come to Britain to examine
the full extent of the problem. The report's release coincides with a government
attempt tomorrow to get the ban on British beef exports lifted with a pledge
to cull up to 125,000 cattle. Douglas Hogg, the agriculture minister, will
face a cool reception as other member states, led by Germany, want the
curbs to remain into the next century.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Manuel Medina Ortega, a Spanish lawyer and the
MEP responsible for drafting the report, said it was as if the EU at all
levels had been governed by omerta, the Italian mafia code of silence,
over BSE. Scientific evidence was kept quiet and scientists who claimed
there was a problem were disbelieved, so the official line was that nothing
happened</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Medina Ortega claimed MacSharry had admitted to the committee that the
commission did not push for action after 1990 because of government pressure.
In March this year British ministers admitted BSE was the most probable
cause of a new strain of <B>Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease</FONT></B>,
a human brain disorder, and the EU imposed a global ban on British beef
exports.<BR>
<BR>
The 19-member committee report will be presented to the European parliament
in 1997. In one internal EU document, Gerard Castille, a former commission
official in charge of consumer protection, claimed that a colleague had
urged the commission to <B>adopt a &quot;policy of
disinformation&quot;</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
One of the most potentially embarrassing revelations con cerns comments
allegedly made by MacSharry at a meeting on September 18, 1990: they were
summarised as: &quot;BSE: stop any meeting.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The committee was also given access to a secret study by the commission's
inspectorate-general last year highlighting <B>shortcomings
in its veterinary services</FONT></B>. It claimed <B>political
pressure governed the awarding of contracts</FONT></B> to European laboratories.<BR>
<BR>
The commission has repeatedly rejected accusations of a cover-up. In his
testimony to the inquiry, MacSharry insisted that if there had been any
failure to implement community directives, then the responsibility lay
in London.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Managing the market was never, I repeat never, given priority over
measures to protect public health,&quot; MacSharry said. &quot;The potential
threat to human health was recognised and given priority treatment from
the very beginning.&quot; This weekend he declined to comment further.<BR>
<BR>
The British government has also denied accusations by members of the committee
that it tried to mislead the public. Keith Meldrum, the chief veterinary
officer, told the inquiry that suggestions of a cover-up were &quot;totally
untrue&quot;.<BR>
<BR>

<HR>
<A NAME="BSE climbdown"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">BSE climbdown</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">By Robert Shrimsley, Chief Political Correspondent<BR>
Telegraph ... Friday 13 December 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>The government is to announce a <B>major climbdown</FONT></B>
on BSE by approving the slaughter of up to 125,000 more cattle, it emerged
last night.<BR>
<BR>
Brussels has <B>refused to lift the EU's ban on British
beef exports</FONT></B> without a wider cull. Ministers are expected to
confirm on Monday that they are ready to go ahead with the deal struck
at the Florence summit in June for a selective cull of those cattle deemed
to be most at risk from BSE.<BR>
<BR>
In September, the Cabinet shelved plans for the selective cull after scientific
evidence showed BSE would be eradicated under the existing scheme to slaughter
beasts 30 month old. But the EU made clear it would not countenance lifting
the ban unless the further slaughter went ahead.<BR>
<BR>
The announcement of the Government's retreat, which could <B>cost
between &pound;150-&pound;200 million</FONT></B> is expected after agreement
was secured from the Treasury on Wednesday evening.<BR>
<BR>
Downing Street <B>attempted to conceal the news</FONT></B>
by saying that the issue had not been discussed at yesterday's Cabinet
meeting but Government sources <B>admitted </FONT></B>last
night that an agreement had been hammered out. The development is likely
to enrage Tory backbenchers who are already furious at the Government's
equivocation over British membership of a European single currency.<BR>
<BR>
Although the figure of 125,000 has been widely used, experts believe the
cull total could be considerably lower as many have already been slaughtered
under the existing scheme. The final figure for the selective slaughter
programme could be nearer 100,000, according to agricultural sources.<BR>
<BR>
One of the problems facing the Government will be tracing the cattle for
slaughter. One area where it will be easier is Northern Ireland, which
could lead the way in having the EU ban lifted - a move which should win
Mr Major added breathing space from the Ulster Unionists as he battles
to keep his Government in office.

<HR>
<A NAME="When safe is not wholly safe"></A><BR>
<H3><CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">When safe is not wholly safe</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<FONT COLOR="009F00">Letters to the Editor<BR><BR>
Financial Times    ...   Thursday December 12 1996</FONT><BR><BR>
Sir,<BR><BR>
Your leader &quot;Of genes and faked beans&quot; (December 6) uses the argument that if a government authority considers something entirely safe for people to eat, it must be entirely safe to eat; and, consequently, any reluctance to eat the product is due to inadequate public education.<BR><BR>
Have we learnt nothing from the BSE fiasco? Did not the government and its scientific advisers originally reassure the country that beef was entirely safe to eat, but are now not so sure that it was.<BR><BR>
Because I am privileged to be reasonably well educated in general science and mathematics I realise that when a government representative says something is safe, what is meant is that there are considered to be no significant indications to the contrary. It does not mean something is in fact safe. By not labelling all products containing, or possibly containing, genetically-modified food the public are being denied a key choice.<BR><BR>
On seconds thoughts, your leader was right: there should be better public education, but by school teachers and not by certain politicians and industrialists.<BR><BR>
Peter Rowbrey-Evans, <BR>30 Lymington Road, <BR>West Hampstead, <BR>London NW6 1HY, UK<BR><BR>

<HR>
<A NAME="More beef goes on Britain's plates"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">More beef goes on Britain's plates</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">by Michael Hornsby<BR>

The Times ... December 10 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT><B>Eating beef is almost back to the level
it held six months before a possible link was made between BSE and</FONT></B>
<B>Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease</FONT></B> <B>in
human beings</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
During the third quarter of the year, household beef consumption was 101g
(3.53 oz) per person per week, 3 per cent down on the same period of 1995,
according to the Ministry of Agriculture.<BR>
<BR>
Between the first and second quarters, consumption plunged by 23 per cent
from 111g to 85g per person per week. This followed the Government's announcement
on March 20 that eating beef infected with BSE was the most likely cause
of a new strain of <B>CJD</FONT></B> in people.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Beef-eating is still 23 per cent lower than in
1994</FONT></B>. The long-term decline is attributed in part to fears of
BSE but also to the cheapness of rival meats such as poultry.<BR>
<BR>

<HR>
<A NAME="Adviser quits over government 'gag'"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Adviser quits over government 'gag'</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">Paul Brown Environment Correspondent<BR>
The Guardian ... Friday, December 6, 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>A government adviser on brain and other nerve damage caused by sheep
dip has <B>resigned from his post because he has
been &quot;gagged&quot;</FONT></B> by a new code of conduct which he says
prevents him telling the full truth in court.<BR>
<BR>
Goran A Jamal, a consultant at the Institute of Neurological Sciences in
Glasgow, had been preparing to be called as an expert witness in cases
where <B>alleged victims of organo-phosphate exposure
were claiming damages</FONT></B>. However, a new code of conduct for the
Medical and Scientific Panel of the Ministry of Agriculture imposed in
February effectively <B>prevented him telling the
court the full truth of what he knew</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Dr Jamal said yesterday: &quot;I was distressed and alarmed at the content
of the code that was imposed upon us. I made it clear it was a resignation
issue for me but they would not relent. There was a conflict between continued
membership and serving justice in a court of law. In effect, they were
forcing me to be economical with the truth.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Ministry of Agriculture instructed sheep farmers
over many years to use organo-phosphate sheep dips even though there was
evidence they could be harmful.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B>There is increasing evidence both from Dr Jamal's institute
and the United States that low level exposure to sheep dip <B>causes
neurological damage</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
It was Dr Jamal's pioneering work that first proved that low level exposure
to organo-phosphates caused <B>nerve damage</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
He said it was not until it became known he was prepared to give evidence
that the code of conduct was imposed.<BR>
<BR>
An all-party group of MPs is backing Dr Jamal. Its chairman, Paul Tyler,
Liberal Democrat MP for North Cornwall, said: &quot;Dr Jamal gave hope
to victims of organo-phosphate poisoning when he was appointed. It was
a major reassurance to them that he would be there to find out the truth
of whether they were entitled to compensation. <B>He
was the only independent member of the committee</FONT></B>.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Ministry insists the evidence available to the committee about damage
should be kept confidential and Dr Jamal accepted that. He believed, however,
that the code prevented him giving other evidence that would have assisted
claimants.<BR>
<BR>
Mr Tyler and Michael Meacher, Labour environment spokesman, are to see
Angela Browning, the agriculture minister, next week to demand publication
of the code.<BR>
<BR>
Mr Meacher said: &quot;A key scientist has been forced to resign as a result
of the ministry's gagging attempts.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
A ministry spokeswoman said the code was intended to provide guidelines
for committee members giving evidence in court. It was intended to prevent
giving information that was not already in the public domain.
<HR>
<A NAME="Chief vet rejects Europe claim of BSE cover-up"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Chief vet rejects Europe claim of
BSE cover-up</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">By Toby Helm and David Brown<BR>

Daily Telegraph ... Wednesday 4 December 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>Keith Meldrum, the Government's Chief Veterinary Officer, yesterday
rejected as &quot;<B>completely and utterly untrue</FONT></B>&quot;
claims from a senior Brussels official that Britain had tried to cover
up the <B>bovine spongiform encephalopathy</FONT></B>
crisis in the early Nineties.<BR>
<BR>
At a hearing of the <B>European Parliament's special
inquiry into the handling of the BSE crisis</FONT></B>, Mr Meldrum gave
a robust defence of the Government's strategy on the epidemic. He made
clear that it had never attempted to hide the seriousness of the problem
from its European Union partners. The denial came as European Commission
efforts to step up the fight against <B>mad cow</FONT></B>
disease were blocked by veterinary experts.<BR>
<BR>
<B>A move to ban from the human and animal food chain
all tissues which could cause BSE or scrapie was rejected by the Standing
Veterinary Committee in Brussels</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Franz Fischler, the Agriculture Commissioner, said he would appeal to EU
agriculture ministers to overturn the &quot;unacceptable&quot; decision.
The new measures already have been implemented in Britain, France and Ireland.<BR>


<HR>
<A NAME="Government on brink of ordering new cattle cull"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Government on brink of ordering
new cattle cull</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">by Michael Hornsby, Agriculture Correspondent<BR>
>
The Times ... December 07 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>Approval for a selective cull of older cattle is <B>expected
next week</FONT></B>, raising hopes of a relaxation of the European Union
ban on British beef .<BR>
<BR>
Plans for the cull were discussed with a delegation from the European Parliament,
which visited Britain to assess the effectiveness of measures to protect
public health against BSE .<BR>
<BR>
Lord Plumb, leader of the Tory MEPs, said after the six-man delegation's
three-day tour ended yesterday: &quot;I am hoping that in a matter of days
we should be getting some announcement on this.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Phillip Whitehead, Labour MEP for Staffordshire and Derby, said that a
lifting of the beef ban would be &quot;much more probable&quot; if the
Government gave the go-ahead for the selective cull.<BR>
<BR>
The European Parliament delegation inspected abattoirs and rendering plants.
They met Roger Freeman, the Cabinet minister in charge of co-ordinating
BSE policy , Ministry of Agriculture officials, scientists, farmers' leaders
and consumer groups.<BR>
<BR>
The slaughter of up to 147,000 cattle identified as being most at risk
of developing BSE was agreed at the EU summit in Florence last June but
the Government put the cull on hold in September, voicing doubts about
its scientific justification.<BR>
<BR>
Some 1.2 million cattle have been incinerated under a separate scheme to
keep those more than 30 months old out of the food chain. This was aimed
at restoring consumer confidence rather than speeding the eradication of
BSE . Cattle under 30 months old are regarded as the least likely to have
eaten the infected meal thought to have caused BSE .<BR>
<BR>
The selective cull would involve older cattle, mainly dairy cows, reared
alongside animals that have already died of BSE and likely to have eaten
the same feed.<BR>
<BR>
Douglas Hogg, the Agriculture Minister, still disputes the scientific grounds
for the selective cull but is understood to have been persuaded by the
political arguments.<BR>
<BR>
Lord Plumb said he believed <B>the selective cull
should involve about 100,000 animals</FONT></B>, fewer than the original
number because some would already have been killed under the over-30-months
scheme. Ian Gardiner, policy director of the National Farmers' Union, said:
&quot;A cull of close to 100,000 animals would be about right, and we want
the the Government to get on with it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Compensation for farmers could top &pound;100
million</FONT></B>. The cost per cow would be high because many animals
would still have years of milking and calving left in them.<BR>
<BR>
The European Parliament delegation was impressed by the BSE safeguards
in place. Friedrich-Wilhelm Graefe zu Baringdorf, a German MEP, said the
export ban would not have been needed had the measures been enforced with
rigour from the outset.

