<CENTER><H3><A NAME="Report">Report</A> on BSE</H3>
</CENTER>House of Commons Agriculture Committee November 1990

<BLOCKQUOTE>This is the Report of the House of Commons Agriculture Committee (a
committee of backbenchers independent of the Government who carried out an
intensive enquiry, in which they took written and verbal evidence and
cross-examined witnesses, including the then Minister (at that time
Gummer), government officials, government scientists, independent
scientists, Southwood, and representatives of numerous organisations.
<P>
The Report was issued in July 1990, but published in November 1990, and
contains full verbatim details of the written and verbal submissions and
the cross-examinations. It is a veritable treasure-house of information
for those who are not satisfied just to accept the versions that have
accumulated down the years.<P>
People in N America can obtain a copy of this report
through the distributor of HMSO publications....
 <PRE>UNIPUB
4611-F Assembly Drive
Langham, Maryland
20706-4319  USA
1-800-233-0504
query@kraus.com</PRE></BLOCKQUOTE>

<HR>

<CENTER><H3>Report on <A NAME="Ceres">Ceres</A> BSE meeting in Washington DC December 12-13.</H3> </CENTER>  <I>The webmaster of this site was present:</I>
<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The meeting was well-attended by a wide mix of people and the
presentations were generally excellent.  Some of more talked-about talks:<P>

Veteran prion researcher Joe Gibbs of NIH laid it on the line about endemic
TSE:  expect it in all mammals at 1 per million per year forever, just from
background mutation.  There's no way of getting rid of it and no way to be
a "BSE-free" country.  Gasps from the renderers, yawns from the moly bio's.<P>

Beth Williams, a veterinary pathologist from Wyoming, gave a good update on
chronic wasting disease, the TSE on the loose in Colorado deer and elk.
The disease is confined to a small region, but the incidence is
disconcertingly high -- a few percent of the population.  Lateral
transmission seems like a done deal here, but how?  They are on a mix of
public-private land, mostly cattle.<P>

I hate process modeling and expected the worst from Dave Harlan's talk, but
actually it was quite good.  Rather than make belligerent all-or-none
assumptions and assertions about BSE titre in the US, Harlan's risk-factor
approach has a goal of a log or two or three reduction.  If the titre is
initially zero, so much the better; if it is not, knock it back as
efficiently as practible by hitting amplification and re-cycling, trying to
get titre below a disease-sustaining threshhold. In other words, that's the
best you can do in the real world -- better get used to it.  (And not just
for BSE.)The other focus besides feeding amplification recycling should be pooled products, like bovine pituitary extracts, for which one sick animal gets pooled with many healthy animals, tainting the whole product.  <P>

US rendering industry scientist Don Franko's position was, if sheep are the
problem, kill the sheep (industry).  If you don't live in the western US,
this could be lost on you: cattle- and sheepmen have been at war for a
century.  Sheep by the millions were driven across the public lands,
leaving devastation in their wake for the less mobile cattle.  Real men
don't herd sheep and all that.<P>

The British delegation (Wilesmith, Bradley, Zeidler, Will) stuck
disappointingly to previously disclosed information, at least at the public
sessions.  It seems that Zeidler and Will are literally the only two who
know the numbers of confirmed nvCJD victims and if you didn't hear it from
them, you didn't hear jack.  There was broad hostility to the British
refusal to release numbers of suspected cases.<P>

I especially enjoyed Gerald Collee's talk; no rubbish from this seasoned
Scottish gentleman.  Collinge said straight out that BSE caused nvCJD and
no one objected; he filled the rest of his time with the  mouse experiment,
now generally viewed as irrelevent.  Telling told me afterwards that the
the strain bands differ by proteolytic nibbling.
<P>
Linda Detwiler of USDA covered her subject most competently.  They have
only gotten onto the immunohistochemistry recently however, so really only
600-700 CNS cows (ok so I got the number wrong) have  been tested  instead
of the 9,000 we hear about.  I see a concern in the training of remote vets:
we should be looking for bovine TSEs, not British BSE.  There's a big
difference, especialy in view of Marsh's results.  Don't expect the
pathology to be remotely the same.  It is also scary to hear Linda describe
how the job they can do is limited by budget -- this is a favorite way of
US industry to throttle environmental enforcement.  USDA needs to get the
money they need in proportion to the task in front of them.  They are way ahead of other countries with IHC and of course there are competing demands on funds.<P>

Kurt Wuethrich (no email) of Switzerland gave an important talk.  His group
has a stranglehold on prion structure, which inconveniently needs a Cray
supercomputer.  He told me flat out that, despite requests from 50 groups
(make that 51), he wasn't giving out the coordinates until April 1997.
[Normally, journals require this before publication;  here, July 11, 1996,
Nature.]   Still, a most charming and likeable fellow.  They showed  cow
and human threaded onto mouse, plus computed the structural impacts of
familial CJD point mutants.  A side view showed prion protein to be a rather thin disk; overall about 35 x 35 x10 angstroms.  All very instructive.  Sounds like there is
more to the solvent-exposed tryptophan than he is letting on to.  He
suggested that the 4 residue beta sheet could be the nucleating seed for a
propagating sheet in prp-sc.  The N-terminal is said to be amorphous, but
they haven't included copper or zinc ion in the mix, which would tie the
repeats together.  In Wuethrich's view, therapy is best directed at surface
blocking on normal prion, because "by the time you get prp-sc formed, it's
too late."<P>
I missed a tacky orchestrated session bashing consumer groups as well as
the banker session, being out in the hallway talking shop with ass't profs
from the Prusiner - Weissman - Harrington empires.<P>

Arpad Somogyi, of the German Consumer Protection Institute, was said to
have given an excellent talk on the precautionary principle, in the
concluding remarks.
<HR WIDTH="35%" ALIGN=Left>
<A HREF="mailto:<eileen@aabb.org>">Eileen Church</A> also took some meeting notes:
<P>

     Collinge stated that a prion protein appears to be central to the BSE
     epidemic but may not be the sole cause.  His biggest concern, of
     course,  is "How does a protein encode phenotype," as evidenced by the
     various strains of SEs.  Some work is being done in that area by Glenn
     Telling et al and will be published in the December 20 Science.<P>


     There was a lot of talk about the British government not doing what it
     should to react to the BSE epidemic.  John Collee stated that
     appropriate actions were taken in a timely way.  He noted that
     problems in enforcement occurred because of cross contamination of
     facilities, continued use of the stored product, and "evasion and
     fraud."  Collee also stated that the govt will conduct a study to try
     to trace back to the "worse than average" rendering mills, although
     this will be difficult, as many smaller mills that sold to larger ones
     are now out of business.<P>
     Collee's view of the route the infectious agent took once consumed as
     follows:<P>
  <PRE>gut
     adsorption to lymphoid tissue in Peyer's patches
     internalization by macrophages
     transport to local lymph nodes
     access to organs such as spleen
     possible transfer via splanchnic nerves to spinal cord
     access to brain with the accumulation of abnormal PrP</PRE>

     According to John Wilesmith, in 1981-82, effective exposure commenced.
     Recycling drove the epidemic, ie, infectious material from infected
     cows reentering the cattle food chain.  Wilesmith and others,
     including Collinge, stated that this recycling was very much a reason
     why the species barrier was broken. (although Colllinge acknowledged
     that the species barrier does still protect to a great extent).<P>

     Wilesmith stated that maternal transmission could not maintain the
     epidemic.  There is no evidence of any mechanism of transmission of BSE
     other than food-borne that was capable of sustaining the epidemic, he
     said. Collinge also agreed that there must be a single source.
     Wilesmith stated that selection bias may have affected the outcome of
     the maternal transmission study.  Wilesmith also stated that he has
     plans for a study to expose British cattle to British sheep scrapie to
     see what happens (ie, whether BSE is linked to scrapie or inherent in
     cattle, as latent or mutant agent).<P>

     Although Zeidler did rehash what is already out there, he previously
     stated (at a November conference) that the v-CJD cases would peak in
     about 7 years.  That indicates that he believes that these cases are
     on the rise, as opposed to being the mid-point of the epidemic.  He
     said the cases we are seeing now reflect 1986-89 exposures to beef. (I
     know these two thoughts do not seem to correspond but that's what he
     said).<P>

     It is also interesting to see the discussion going on now re: the
     number of v-CJD cases and their future pattern.  That was also much
     discussed at the meeting.  It was explained that there could have been
     many people exposed, but they did not develop the disease, for
     whatever reason (no genetic disposition, not enough infectious agent,
     species barrier, true resistance, etc).  If that was the case, then it
     is possible that the cases we are seeing today reflect the results of
     peak exposure, and will fall or will rise slightly and fall.  On the
     other hand, these cases may represent just the beginning of a much
     larger epidemic that will peak at much higher levels.  What appears
     unclear is where these human cases correspond to the curve
     representing the cattle epidemic.  Many stated it is too early to
     tell. Although it appeared to me that many were operating on the
     assumption that there are more cases to come, none really tried to
     predict the future magnitude of the outbreak.<P>

<PRE> Other items thrown out at meeting:<P>
     --pigs don't seem to be susceptible to SEs
     --fetal calf blood does not appear to transmit BSE to mice
     --Frank Bastian stated his theory that spiroplasma(s) are the agents
     of SE transmission

     Collee also added these other possible routes of infection (in cattle)
     --ingestion
     --wound contamination
     --inhalation
     --nasal/mucosal  (If you've ever seen cattle eat MBM, this should not
     be a surprise)</PRE>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="Research">Research</A> News and Gossip</H3>
</CENTER>
On-going research highlights  from Steven Dealler's <A HREF="http://www.airtime.co.uk/bse/welcome.htm">web page</A>:
<P>

#OC9038. Investigation of the role of the embryo in maternal transmission of scrapie in sheep . 
      I have been told that the embryo appears to be come infected in utero and that this
      result is soon to be published. <P>

# SE1811, SE1819: Injection of bovine embryos with BSE/PrP infectivity,  BSE embryo transfer studies 
     The worry is that BSE might be transferred from one cow to another by the embryo
      and might be carried to foreign countries by it. <P>

#OC8946  Experimental transmission of feline spongiform encephalopathy to mice. 
      This may well have been completed already and we have evidence that experts have the
      data. <P>

# SE1805, SE1806 Transmissibility of BSE to domestic fowl by injection and oral exposure to brain homogenate<P>

# SE1802, SE1803 Transmissibility of BSE to pigs by injection and oral exposure to brain homogenate<P>

#SE1821 Comparative efficiencies of the bioassay of BSE infectivity in cattle and mice. 
      This has vertually been completed and a species barrier of about 1000 was found.
      What it showed, of course was that mice could not be used easily as BSE assays and this
      made much of the previous work of the groups looking for BSE infectivity in tissues
      invalid. <P>

* Information is now appearing that scrapie had been passed to other animals by
      the USDA. The data does not seem to have been published and some of it is really quite important.
      Exactly which animals I am not allowed to say but this may be revealed in USDA
      documents. <P> 

* Canadian woman dies of CJD -seems to be the new variant form. 
      She was around 63 yr old i.e. not of the young group of CJD-2 cases that we have seen so far. The worry is
      that she is also not Met-Met at PrP 129, that being an indication that we are all open
      to infection but in people with the wrong codon it just takes longer to appear. She was
      living in the UK until around 1994 and was not a vegetarian. <P>
* The MAFF are now looking in the fields in the UK for mites that may carry prions. The amazing results from Staten Island showing that the mites from the land in Iceland
      actually had enough prion chemical to be found using blotting, must mean that the
      agent might be kept in the land by these arachnids. The worry is, of course that the
      land might also keep BSE. 

<HR>

<CENTER><H3>International <A NAME="trade">trade</A> and human or animal
diseases: a .</H3>
</CENTER> BLANCOU, J., MESLIN, F.-X. <BR>
Selected Plenary and Symposium Sessions<BR>
XXV Congress of the World Veterinary
Association<BR>
Yokohama, Japan, 3-9 September 1995.
<BLOCKQUOTE>Since ancient times, the international movement of animals or human
beings has been an occasion for the exchange of pathogens. The
authors examine various concrete examples of the most serious
incidents which have occurred from antiquity to the present day.
The history of disease incidents is studied in relation to trade in
animals and animal products: the international transmission of
<B>pathogens linked to trade in cattle and products of bovine origin:</B>
<P>
* rinderpest<BR>
* foot-and-mouth disease<BR>
* bovine pleuropneumia<BR>
* cowdriosis<BR>
* bovine spongiform encephalopathy<BR>
* African swine fever <BR>
* African horse sickness<BR>
* sheep pox
<P>
To illustrate the
economic consequences of disease incidents associated with trade in
animals and animal products, examples are given of <B>economic losses
recorded from 1766 (875,000 cattle died from rinderpest in Europe)</B>
to 1991-1994 (more than <B>three million pigs died or were killed due
to classical swine fever (hog cholera)</B> in Europe during this three-
year period, representing over US$ 1 billion in losses).
The consequences of international movement for human health are
discussed by providing examples of human diseases resulting from
the movement of people since ancient times (cholera, dengue,
influenza, plague, yellow fever, etc.) and of those resulting from
the introduction of animal or animal products (brucellosis, rabies,
tuberculosis, etc.).
<P>
Tables and figures are presented showing data from antiquity to the
20th century. The authors conclude by emphasing the increasingly
serious risks of transferring human or animal diseases world-wide
and the necessity of taking the most appropriate measures to reduce
these risks: strengthening veterinary and medical surveillance
systems, and conducting research into and development of new
vaccines.
<HR>
<A NAME="Student is 13th victim of new CJD strain"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Student is 13th victim of new CJD
strain</FONT></H3><I><PRE>[Charities involved with CJD. The CJD support network is administered through the Alzheimer's Disease Society at the
following address.:

The Secretary, CJD Support Network
Alzheimer's Disease Society, Gordon House
10 Greencoat Place, London SW1P 1PH 
Telephone: 0171 306 0606 ]</PRE></I>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">By Nigel Bunyan<BR>
<BR>
Telegraph ... Tuesday 17 December 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT><B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">A 19-YEAR-OLD student has become the 13th
person in Britain to die from the virulent new strain of Creutzfeld-Jakob
disease</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Victoria Lowther, who had been preparing to take up a university place,
<B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">died in a Carlisle hospice four months after first
showing signs of the disease. She had no connection with cattle or the
meat industry</FONT></B>. Miss Lowther, of Abbotsford Drive, Carlisle,
had been treated in the neurology unit of the Royal Victoria Hospital,
Newcastle upon Tyne, before being transferred to the Eden Valley Hospice,
where she died on Nov 19.<BR>
<BR>
Ian Morton, coroner for north-east Cumbria, said yesterday he had decided
not to hold an inquest because medical authorities <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">were
satisfied that</FONT></B> <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B> <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">had
been the cause of her illness</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Miss Lowther had been a pupil at Lime House School in Dalston, Cumbria.
She left to take a car sales job pending a move to university.<BR>
<BR>
William Brotherton, chairman of the school, said: &quot;She was one of
those girls who had it all. She had good looks. She was a stunning girl
- bright, clever, very popular. In a matter of six months she slid downhill
rapidly.&quot;
<HR>
<A NAME="CJD blamed for woman's death"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">CJD blamed for woman's death</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">by Russell Jenkins<BR>
<BR>
Times ... December 17 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>A Young woman is thought to be the latest person to have died from
the new strain of <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">CJD</FONT></B> blamed on eating
BSE-infected meat, <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">especially beefburgers</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Victoria Lowther, 19, the daughter of a hotel owner in Carlisle, Cumbria,
<B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">died last month in a hospice four months after
first complaining of repeated headaches. From a bright teenager heading
for university, she quickly degenerated into a wheelchair-bound invalid,
dependent on carers</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
The rapid decline is consistent with the symptoms of the new variant of
Creutzfeld-Jakob disease, which hits younger people with devastating results.
The Department of Health said last night that there were <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">14
confirmed cases of the variant strain</FONT></B>, which government scientists
have linked to &quot;<B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">mad cow</FONT></B>&quot;
disease. <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">Two of the confirmed victims are still
alive</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
Every new case raises <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">fears of an epidemic among
young people</FONT></B> who ate cheap beef products in the late 1980s.
Miss Lowther had no connection with cattle or meat production.
<P>
<H4>Listserve Commentary</H4>

<I>Vicky Rimmer was the first person in the
UK to show these symptoms. She is still alive, in a coma. The brailn biopsy was
performed  because doctors were so confused about what the disease
was. After all, they'd not come across it before in someone who had not had
a brain op or HGH.
<P>
 One point about Vicky Lowther, the latest to die: if the newspaper
report (Daily Mail in the UK) is accurate, <B>the course of the disease was
unusually rapid: four months from onset to death.</B> That dosen't fit the
symptoms seen in other vCJD victims, who had something like 18 months from
onset of clinical symptoms (depression, etc) to death. Wondering if
it's a variation in the disease, or if the press reports got the timing
wrong.</I>
<HR>
<A NAME="Inability to talk about fears leads to farm suicides"></A><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#009F00">Inability to talk about fears leads
to farm suicides</FONT></H3>
<FONT COLOR="#009F00">By David Brown, Agriculture Editor<BR>
<BR>
Daily Telegraph ... Thursday 5 December 1996<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>Loneliness in the farmhouse is taking its toll on the lives of farmers,
according to a new report.<BR>
<BR>
While countryside isolation is well recorded as a main cause of depression
and suicide, researchers at Oxford say that more than a third of farmers
who kill themselves have marriage difficulties or other family problems.<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">The survey tarnishes the image of the farmer's
wife as loyal, caring and loving by revealing that many did not know anything
was wrong because &quot;they haven't spoken to their husbands for years&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B>The report, released to coincide with yesterday's official launch
of the Rural Stress Network, an umbrella organisation designed to reduce
suicides among farmers and their families, shows that personal problems
in the home are the biggest factor behind the deaths after business worries.<BR>
<BR>
Dr Aslog Malmberg, of Oxford's Department of Psychiatry, told the Royal
College of Psychiatry in London: &quot;Many wives were not aware anything
was wrong. <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">One woman said she had not spoken to
her husband for 10 years</FONT></B>.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
She said many farmers faced more than one problem with business, marriage
and family all interlocked. &quot;Because of the nature of the way farms
are run, many problems overlap. If there are financial problems it will
affect the marriage and if there is divorce, or children want to buy out
of the business, it affects the value of the property,&quot; she added.<BR>
<BR>
In carrying out a study, backed by the Department of Health, Dr Malmberg
confirmed research showing that farmers were more likely than any other
profession to commit suicide and said the beef crisis could worsen matters.<BR>
<BR>
Figures released yesterday showed that <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">650 farmers
killed themselves in England and Wales in the 11 years up to 1992</FONT></B>.
But they also revealed that <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">farmers' wives suffered
stress and depression, with 147 of them committing suicide in the same
period</FONT></B>.<BR>
<BR>
The survey looked at 84 farmers who had killed themselves and found that
53 per cent had experienced a variety of problems with work in the year
before their deaths, with 22 per cent suffering financial strain. Thirty-five
per cent had marital trouble and 28 per cent family problems.<BR>
<BR>
Dr Malmberg said the researchers had looked at coroners' reports on farmers
and had interviewed relatives to try to identify factors leading to death.
The 84 farmers - all but three aged around 56 - were &quot;probably suffering
from moderate or severe depression at the time of the suicide which had
gone unnoticed or was being undertreated&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
Janet Pugh, a farmer's wife from Hertfordshire who works as a volunteer
with the Samaritans, is a founder-trustee of the Rural Stress Network.
She said: &quot;Farmers, particularly the older ones, find it difficult
to talk over their problems with their wives. They see it as a weakness
to ask for help.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Richard Kerkham, head of the Samaritans' rural group network, said: &quot;Since
March 20 when the beef crisis broke, farmers are talking to each other
more about their difficulties. They wouldn't normally do that with their
immediate neighbour - because he is a rival - but, with BSE, all livestock
farmers are in the same boat.&quot;<BR>
<HR>
<CENTER><H3>CJD <A NAME="referrals">referrals</A></H3></CENTER><I>Taken from the CJD Unit home page in December 1996.  A controversy has arisen because the Unit is refusing to release the number of suspected cases of nvCD -- webmaster</I>
