<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>BBC on BSE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><CENTER><H3>BBC on BSE</H3>
</CENTER>November 18, 1996
<P>


<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>(JO UNWIN):  Inside this test-tube is enough purified BSE to kill 10 million cows.  It now seems certain that it can kill humans too.   But the scientific communityfailed to predict that we would be susceptible.   They had been baffled by this extraordinary and mysterious agent of disease.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">DR PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  The infectious agent is almost immortal and it may be impossible to destroy it.   These agents are incredibly resistant to almost everything we throw at them.   They resist alcohol, they resist boiling, they resist  gluteraldehyde.<p>

<FONT COLOR="996633">DR  DAVID TAYLOR</FONT>:  Ultraviolet radiation, gamma radiation. microwave radiation, potassium permanganate, chlorine dioxide, hydrogen peroxide.
<P>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  They resist hospital detergents, ionising radiation, even autoclaving.<p>

<FONT COLOR="996633">DAVID TAYLOR</FONT>:  Well we have here for example a hot air oven which runs at the same sort of temperatures as your domestic oven at home which you would reasonably expect to kill conventional bacteria and viruses.   However if you cook these types of agents even at prolonged times in this type of oven you just don't kill them, which means that of course if you have meat infected with such agents you cannot rely it to kill these agents at all.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  We thought it would be interesting to see what would happen if we buried some of these agents and so I ground up some scrapie brain and mixed it with soil, put it in a flowerpot enclosed it in a cage and used my own garden as a burial site, right here, and what we found was that a good deal of the infectivity remained in the soil after 3 years. We exposed it to temperatures that turned it to ash and it did not entirely kill the agent and so every known pathogen of man would have been destroyed by this process and this was not.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  This extraordinary organism was studied long before BSE appeared, because BSE is only a new form of an ancient group of brain diseases, called spongiform encephalopathies.All spongiform encephalopathies are caused by the same infectious agent.  Many species of animal, other than cows, are vulnerable to it, but the disease has always baffled scientists.   We know that the infectious agent accumulates in the brain over many years and eventually destroys brain cells.  The damage is slow but irreparable.   It always ends in death.   Under the microscope the brains of all animals suffering from these diseases have the same distinctive holes that turns the brain to sponge.   In humans the disease is called CJD, Creutzfeldt Jakob Disease. We don't know why, but every person on the planet from Africa to America, rich or poor, vegetarian or carnivore, is at risk of getting CJD in old age.  That's been known for decades, but CJD can infect humans in different ways.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">PROF. JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  We can think of CJD as coming in three forms.   The majority of CJD, about 85%, is what we call sporadic CJD. It's present at similar frequency all over the world.   The lifetime risk of getting CJD is about 1 in 50,000 wherever you look around, around the world, whether there's BSE there or not.   Then there are these cases that have arisen from tragic medical accidents where people have been accidentally exposed to something that's contaminated with CJD.   For instance, children that were treated for growth deficiencies by giving them growth hormone that was contaminated with CJD.   Those are also very rare cases, thankfully, 20 or 30 people probably in the United Kingdom.   There are the inherited forms.  These run in families, they're extremely rare.   None of these three forms of CJD, as far as we are aware, have anything to do with, with BSE.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  But there is one more form of the disease and it may shed light on our current fears over BSE because it caused the first, and up till now, only epidemic of spongiform encephalopathy in human history.   Early this century a strange new disease appeared in the tribal highlands of Papua New Guinea.   It was called kuru - it means to tremble with fear.   Within years it had wiped out thousands of people in one particular tribe.  It was unknown elsewhere in the world.  In 1957 scientists went to the highlands to try and find the source of the disease.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  They found a population that was dying from this disease, but primarily affecting children of both sexes equally and young adult women.   The first symptoms were a little incoordination, a little stagger when they walked.   Little by little over a period of months this became sufficiently severe so that they were unable to walk unaided.   In time the people were unable even to stand and therefore became helpless.  Most people with this disease died within  9 months.   
<P>
Because this disease had this peculiar distribution of age and sex, one of the things you think about is endocrine problems, one of the things you think about is genetic problems you think about toxic causes, you think about malnutrition.  All of these were considered, all were studied in detail and none of them proved out to be correct.   The answer turned out in fact to be very simple:
these people were cannibals. It was clearly being transmitted from person to person by cannibalism.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  This tribe ate their dead relatives as a mark of respect during funeral rites.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  This was not warfare cannibalism, this was loving cannibalism.  In the course of cannibalistic ritual feasting the body was cut up into parts and the men reserved the best parts for themselves and the best parts were muscle. The remaining parts of the body, including brain and pancreas and liver and kidney and intestines, were eaten by the women and the children.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  The disease was passed on when women and children ate infected brains.  When they developed kuru and died, they were then ritually eaten, and so the epidemic escalated, an epidemic of human spongiform encephalopathy.   This tragic cycle was broken when cannibalism on the island ended in the 60s, but the incubation period of this disease is so long that the last victims are still dying today.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  The solution to the way kuru was passed from human to human, together with a number of laboratory experiments conducted over the years since, have, without any question, brought persuasive evidence to the idea that infection can be transmitted by feeding.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  In 1986, a new form of the disease struck British cattle.   It had never been seen in cows before. Brain slides from infected cattle showed the same distinctive holes of all spongiform encephalopathies, and we were eating those cattle brains.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  I think the two key questions then revolved around:  what is the nature of the infectious agent in precise molecular terms, what is it, and secondly, of course, the, the burning question became:  can BSE transmit to humans, and are we going to see an epidemic of human disease following exposure to BSE?<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  But scientists working in the field had no answers.  So little was known about these diseases and the agent that caused them that researchers could only guess what the danger to humans might be.<p>

DR ADRIANO AGUZZI:  The theoretical impossibility that BSE might be not contagious but might indeed provoke a disease in humans, was always there and every serious scientist has pointed it out that there was a possibility there.  However, however it was unlikely and I still maintain that, that it was reasonable to, to assume that it would be very unlikely.   The reason is sheep scrapie.   Sheep scrapie has been with us for a long time and yet there is no linkage of consumption of sheep brain with Creutzfeldt Jakob Disease, so it appears that there there is a very strict species barrier.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  Scrapie is the sheep form of spongiform encephalopathy.  It exists all over the world.  We've had scrapie in Britain for 200 years.  It's fatal in sheep, but seems to be harmless to us.   Scientists were confident that even eating scrapie-infected brains would not cause disease in humans.   But government scientists believed that cows were susceptible to scrapie, and that's what started the BSE epidemic.  Cows were fed a cheap protein supplement to increase their milk yield.   That supplement included the rendered carcasses of scrapie infected sheep.  The theory is that through this feed the disease crossed the species barrier from sheep into cows.<p>

Infected cows were then rendered down and fed back to more cows, escalating the whole epidemic.  It was a kind of cattle cannibalism, chillingly reminiscent of kuru. For the first two years of the epidemic cows dying of BSE could be slaughtered and sent for human consumption.   Their brains ended up in burgers and sausages, meat pies and patties.  In 1988, the government called on the scientific community for advice.   An eminent group of scientists was asked to study all the research on spongiform encephalopathies, most of it about scrapie and decide whether BSE was a risk to humans.   The committee was headed by the zoologist, Professor <FONT COLOR="0000DD">RICHARD SOUTHWOOD</FONT>.<p>

<FONT COLOR="0000DD">PROF SIR RICHARD SOUTHWOOD</FONT>:  Back in 1988 it was very difficult to be confident in one's recommendations.  The amount of information that we had about spongiform encephalopathies was very small.  We knew there was this disease in sheep fairly widespread called scrapie which had been around for 100-200 years.  it didn't seem to be causing a great deal of problems in the human population, so we based our conclusion that the chance of transmission to humans was remote on the long experience of scrapie, but we emphasised that if that assumption was wrong, the consequences were grave and therefore steps should be taken to assume that we were wrong. But cattle can be infected with BSE for years without showing any signs of illness.   They could be sold and slaughtered looking healthy but actually incubating the disease.   So the only way to safeguard human food entirely would be to remove, in the abattoir, the most dangerous organs - the brain and spinal cord - from every cattle carcass.  The Southwood Committee did not call for this ban.  Bringing in any of these bans, of course, does pose considerable practical problems.  One is imposing additional costs on all those concerned.
We didn't at that time think a specified offal ban was crucial.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  The Southwood Committee decided only to ban offal from baby food.   Potentially infected cow brain could still go into adult food.<p>

<FONT COLOR="0000DD">RICHARD SOUTHWOOD</FONT>:  We were particularly concerned with baby food because we thought there could be a relationship between the size of the body and the size of the dose and that a much smaller dose which could be possible for a small amount of brain material getting into the food could possibly infect a young baby and so that's why we picked on baby food rather than on adult food.<p>

DR HUGH FRASER:  It really was probably an inappropriate thing to do, to suggest that just the, the ban of brain tissue should be confined to baby food. <p>

We knew from our work in animals, and particularly in laboratory rodents, that the <B>young animal quite unexpectedly was actually largely resistant to infection with these agents and it was actually the older animals of these species which were more susceptible to scrapie infection than the new-born and the neonate.</B><p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  Nine months after the Southwood Committee reported, the government extended the offals ban to all foods, to protect adults as well as babies.   But some abattoirs, perhaps believing that BSE was not a risk to humans, did not fully enforce the ban.  We now know that infected material was still getting into human food until the end of 1995.<p>

<FONT COLOR="0000DD">RICHARD SOUTHWOOD</FONT>: <B> I've often reflected as to whether we wrote our report in too reassuring a way and in some way this dimmed the urgency which was necessary and obviously one regrets that.</B><p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  This reassurance was soon echoed by the government and the meat industry who used it as their scientific guide and justification.<p>

DAVID MacLEAN:  We rely on Professor Southwood and his independent experts who said the theoretical risk of BSE was remote.<p>

KEITH MELDRUM:  We have to base our knowledge of the disease on scrapie.
We are fairly confident that there is no risk to human health.
The public is not at risk from BSE.<p>

<FONT COLOR="0000DD">RICHARD SOUTHWOOD</FONT>:  You may wonder why we were not more alarmist in our report, but you must remember that at that time we were dealing with a very rare disease in cattle, a human disease that was, is, is, and has remained very rare, most people had never heard of it, and if we had been too alarmist we were in danger of upsetting the whole of the meat industry in Britain and elsewhere in Europe.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  But research carried out since the 1970s should have rung alarm bells about the very basis of the Southwood Committee's reassurance -- the link with scrapie.   This research indicated that scrapie and all spongiform encephalopathies can change fundamentally when they cross into a new species.<p>

HUGH FRASER:  We've certainly known since the mid-1970s that when scrapie infection is transmitted to and passaged within a new species that strain characteristics and disease characteristics can change and that a, a phenomenon analogous to mutation can occur and that as a result of that you can generate a strain with new properties, with new characteristics, with altered neuropathology even, and  even with an altered host range.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  Let's assume that BSE is the result of rendered recycled scrapie in the food chain of cattle.  There is not a shred of evidence to date that scrapie has ever caused CJD in humans, but scrapie passaged or, or going into cattle might change the host range of the infection and therefore we cannot predict whether BSE would be, or would not be infectious for humans.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  The Southwood Committee did recognise this possibility even as they wrote their report.<p>

<FONT COLOR="0000DD">RICHARD SOUTHWOOD</FONT>:  We of course had no way of knowing at that time whether the BSE agent was exactly the same as the scrapie agent.  Work since has shown that it does actually perform in a slightly different way to the scrapie agent.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  The first clue came in 1990 when domestic cats died of BSE.   <B>Cats, like humans, had never been susceptible to scrapie.</B>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  It was certainly concerning when domestic cats developed a spongiform encephalopathy and we
now know that that is BSE that was acquired by these domestic cats and now by quite a few wild cats kept in zoos and some other wild animals kept in zoological gardens, and so <B>that really indicated that BSE had a quite different host range than scrapie that it was infecting different species that had not gone down with scrapie in the past</B>, so that was certainly a cause for concern for me.   Of course that doesn't tell us that humans are going to be at any higher risk, but it does tell us that BSE is rather different than scrapie.

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  Over the years the list of susceptible species grew longer.   Scientists grew more worried.  BSE crossed into almost every species exposed to it.  This was extremely unusual.<p>

ADRIANO AGUZZI:  BSE has a lot of very special features which we have never seen before in other types of spongiform encephalopathy.  First of all it's very promiscuous, meaning that it's not choosy in the type of host that it will affect, it can infect basically all species where this has been tried.   It will go into, into mice, it will go into cats, it will go into monkeys, so we are witnessing a very special disease that has different features from the other spongiform encephalopathies we knew before and therefore we have to deal with the problem that it might even infect humans.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  People eating potential BSE infected material were eating a new disease.   They weren't eating scrapie anymore.   <B>No the original scrapie that may or may not have triggered off the epidemic, was long gone.</B>
<P>


<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  From the beginning many scientists had been reassured by the link with scrapie and thought it unlikely that BSE would cross the species barrier into humans, but with the scrapie link gone, they faced the reality that we knew little about this new disease and had no clue as to whether it could infect humans.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  The species barrier between cows and humans was unknown.  You can't just assume that it's going to be an absolute one.  Of course we can't measure it because that would involve injecting humans with BSE which clearly we wouldn't do.<p>


DR MOIRA BRUCE:  It's difficult to see how directly we could ever have that information as we can't do experiments on humans.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  But a human experiment has been done.   Millions of us ate infected beef.   We've been part of a vast experiment for the last 10 years.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  With BSE I think we are looking at the emergence of a disease which
may affect significant numbers of people, and I think we have to understand in precise molecular terms the nature of this infectious agent and work out how to kill it.
<P>

<FONT COLOR="996633">DAVID TAYLOR</FONT>:  These agents seem to disobey basic rules of biology.<p>

DAVID BOLTON:  It goes against everything that we've been taught.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:The infectious agent is certainly unique in the world of biology.<p>

ADRIANO AGUZZI:  The first question what interests almost everybody is:  what is the nature of the infectious agent, what is the agent that causes scrapie and BSE, Creutzfeldt Jakob and, and this has been very enigmatic
and this question: what is the nature of the agent, this is this is clearly the Nobel Prize question, this is what everybody's trying to answer and there is a lot of competition.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  The mystery of this infectious agent made it difficult to predict whether BSE would be a risk to humans.  But for decades before BSE arrived, scientists had been searching, in vain, for the agent of spongiform encephalopathies.<p>

MOIRA BRUCE:  Scientists have been working on this disease for a roundabout 50 years.   It's a very difficult disease to work with and one of the main reasons was that we don't know for sure what the agent is, so we don't have a direct way of, of identifying it.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  Most infections are caused by bacteria or viruses which replicate and spread disease.  They can be seen under the microscope and the way they work is well understood.   For  years scientists searched for a virus as the cause of spongiform encephalopathies, but the agent that causes these diseases remain invisible.  It could not be seen, nor even detected by any conventional method, and it had an even stranger quality, one that would prove crucial to understanding its true identity. In 1967, Professor TIKVA ALPER tried to find out what would kill the agent.   She took a solution of infected brain tissue and placed it in front of a source of radiation.  She bombarded this sample with a dose large enough to destroy any virus or bacterium, in fact, large enough to destroy any known infectious organism.   But this lethal radiation had little effect.   The mysterious agent was still active.<p>

SCIENTIST:  The results of Dr. TIKVA ALPER and her colleagues was so remarkable that we tried to repeat them and I must say we've repeated them twice with absolutely identical experimental results.<p>

<FONT COLOR="996633">DAVID TAYLOR</FONT>:  The extreme resistance of these agents to all manner of inactivation procedures does tell us that they're quite unlike conventional bacterium or viruses and that they are some novel type of living organism.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  Scientists tried to identify this novel organism by taking a solution of infected brain material and studying it under an electron microscope so powerful that it could magnify objects 100,000 times.   Even the smallest virus can be seen using this machine.   After years of scanning brain samples, in 1981 scientists finally had their first glimpse of the killer. But these fibrils contain millions of particles of the infectious agent.  Even with this powerful electron microscope it was still impossible to see and identify a tiny individual particle, or to know what these fibrils were made of.   The only way to identify the nature of the agent without actually seeing it was to analyse it chemically. The lab in the forefront of purifying infected brain samples was Stan Prusiner's in San Francisco.  In 1982 there was one scientist there whose job was to discover chemical clues about the agent.<p>

DR DAVID BOLTON:  When I came to San Francisco what we wanted to look for was what was unique about a sample from the diseased brain that was not in the normal brain, what, what component, what molecule would be in that diseased brain that was never in the normal brain, and so I did some experiments where I looked at proteins and separated these proteins using a gel to separate them by their size and they give little different bands on the gel, and when I did that I didn't really expect to find anything right off the bat and, and after one of the experiments I went into the dark room to develop the film and I was very surprised when I saw this, and I knew when I saw this gel that this had to be it.  There's a fuzzy band that's here in the gel that's in each of the three samples from the diseased brain, and it's not in the samples from the normal brain, and this is exactly what we had been looking for.  We and everybody else had been looking for some sort of a key, some kind of a molecule that we could say was in the diseased brain and not in the normal brain and that really forced us to conclude that this protein is part of the agent, in fact might be the only component of the agent.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  In discovering this protein the lab felt they had finally cornered the elusive infectious agent.  The scientists called it the PRP protein, but it became known as a "prion".
But finding the prion didn't solve the mystery, it deepened it.   This key molecule wasn't a fragment of a virus or bacterium, the normal agents of disease, it was simply a protein and proteins can't be infectious.<p>

PROF. CHARLES WEISSMAN:  1982 I was at a lecture by Stan Prusiner in Australia and that was the first time I heard him speak and he was talking about these so-called "prion diseases", scrapie in particular, and he proposed that a protein was the infectious agent and that seemed extremely odd and very novel and I was not really quite sure whether this could be true.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  For a protein to be an infectious agent was a scientific heresy.  Apart from water, our bodies are mainly made up of proteins.   They're tiny, far smaller than the smallest virus.   There are literally thousands of different kinds of protein and each has a unique role.  Some digest our food, some absorb our oxygen, others form neurotransmitters in the brain that allow us to think.   But proteins can't cause an infectious disease.  That's because they contain no DNA, no nucleic acid and therefore they cannot replicate. Nothing on the planet replicates without nucleic acid. nucleic acid provides the only mechanism by which all life multiplies.   It is the nucleic acid inside every bacterium and virus that allows it to replicate and cause disease.   How could this mysterious protein cause disease without any means of copying itself.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  To the best of my knowledge, all infectious agents, all pathogens require the participation of nucleic acid in order to multiple to replicate.  The idea, therefore, that replication could occur without nucleic acid is heresy.<p>

DAVID BOLTON:  We couldn't figure out how could a protein replicate if it doesn't have a nucleic acid?<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  This puzzled scientists for years, but tantalisingly an answer had already been worked out 30 years ago.  The theory had lain buried in the literature, almost forgotten, because at the time it was written in 1967 it was dismissed as too outlandish.<p>

DAVID BOLTON:  I started thinking about several years before when I had been doing a literature review and looking in some journals in the library at a paper and I was looking actually up one paper that was written about the nature of the scrapie agent and when I went to photocopy it on the second page of that paper there was another paper and it was<B> by a mathematician named J.S. Griffiths</B> and in this paper he talks about self-replication in scrapie which is one of these diseases, and he outlines three ways that a protein alone could replicate and cause disease. 
<P>
Now he came up with the idea that you would have two different forms of the protein - one was abnormal, disease-causing, a rogue protein if you will, and the other was a normal protein that would be in the cell or in the brain of a normal person, and the essential part of the theory was that the abnormal form of the protein could bind to the normal form and convert it, change its structure to make it an abnormal or a disease-causing protein, and now you can see that if one molecule binds to another molecule and converts it, now you have two molecules of abnormal protein, and two combined to two more and have four, and so on and so on until you have thousands and millions of abnormal proteins in the brain and pretty soon then you have disease, you have so much abnormal protein in the brain that it would cause disease and cause neurones to die. 
<P>
The most amazing thing was that the paper was published in 1967.  He was a mathematician, wrote this one paper, never published anything again in scrapie.   The insight was really very astounding that someone back then with so little information could see a way that a protein could be an infectious agent.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  What Griffiths proposed was an abstract theory, and it was completely ignored by the scientific community.  But over the years clues have been found that indicate he may have had the answer all along.   In 1985 it was discovered that there were two forms of the PRP protein, just as Griffiths had predicted.
<P>
One was a normal protein, genetically manufactured by every animal and found throughout the healthy body. Like all other proteins, it seemed to have some valuable function.  Certainly it never caused disease, but something could trigger this normal, healthy protein to mutate, to change form into a prion. This form of the protein, the prion, is identical down to the last amino acid, but abnormal   This new shape makes it so chemically stable that it resists heat and disinfectants, and because it's simply a protein without nucleic acid it can survive huge doses of radiation because radiation kills by destroying nucleic acid.   Once in its abnormal form, the protein seems to have the unique ability to corrupt any healthy PRP proteins that it comes into contact with and turn them into prions too.  This is not replication, it's conversion.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  It's a very strange observation that you have these two quite different forms of the same protein with quite different properties.   One of them is a killer.   If, if this protein is present in your brain you're in serious trouble.   The other one is a normal constituent of all our brains and obviously understanding how one converts into the other and in the longer term how to stop it is, is a tremendous puzzle.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  Although there are still puzzles, we do know that, once converted, prions link together in long, indestructible chains that accumulate in the brain and somehow create the devastating holes that kill. If this theory is confirmed, it will be a revolution in biology, but so far it remains unproven.   No-one has yet found a convincing explanation for how prions corrupt normal proteins and so the protein only hypothesis remains controversial.<p>

ADRIANO AGUZZI:  The protein only hypothesis is, is beautiful.<p>

DAVID BOLTON:  I very strongly believe in the protein only hypothesis.<p>

ADRIANO AGUZZI:  It's intellectually very appealing.<p>

CHARLES WEISSMAN:  I became largely convinced that in fact the protein only hypothesis is true.<p>

ADRIANO AGUZZI:  It should not go unmentioned that the protein only hypothesis in its current incarnation does not explain everything.<p>

HUGH FRASER  The idea that it is an infectious protein is  an exciting and curious idea but it's one which I do not accept.<p>

MOIRA BRUCE:  It may be that the agent is just a protein, but if it is, it's a quite extraordinary protein and it behaves in a quite extraordinary way.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  This has been an extremely controversial area of science.  Prions are new infectious agents and there's been a very rapid evolution of ideas and I think BSE has arrived on the scene in the midst of this scientific controversy and of course that's added to the complexities of, of, of making these sort of risk assessments.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  In the late 1980s, while people were eating infected food, scientists were still trying to unravel the mysteries of the infectious agent.   The prion controversy had split the scientific community and this division only made the search for answers more difficult.   If the prion hypothesis was right, it was crucial to understand whether the cow prions in BSE could infect humans.  To do this meant deciphering the strange rules of the species barrier. All animals make slightly different forms of PRP protein.  The more closely related the species the more similar their PRP is.   The key to the species barriers between all these animals lies in how easily the prions from one type of animal can lock on to the proteins of another and turn them into prions too.   This is what determines how easily one species can infect another, but it doesn't always depend on how similar their proteins are.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  And it really is quite an unpredictable phenomenon.
By and large <B>we tend to think that animals that are more closely related in evolutionary terms are going to be easier to transmit the disease to, but it's not always like that at all. </B>  For instance it can be extremely difficult to transmit the disease between mice and hamsters which are quite closely related species.   In seems to be relatively easy to transmit BSE to mice which are
quite distantly related species, so you know there are really some very strange rules operating here and the only way to find out is to do the experiments.  You can't just sit down with a piece of paper and work out how easy it will go from one species to another.  It's something you have to determine experimentally.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  First of all scientists tried infecting primates whose PRP protein was close to humans, but when the marmosets and macaques died of BSE it still wasn't proof that humans were susceptible.   These animals' PRP, though similar, was still too different from ours to be a realistic human model.   A closer primate to humans is the chimpanzee.   They were never tested.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  Had this experiment been done 10 years ago we would have that answer today.  As it is the experiment, to the best of my knowledge, has still not been done.  It is being discussed and I'm afraid when the answer comes, which will probably be positive, it won't have any significance at all because we'll already know the answer.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  In the early 90s scientists in America decided to try a different approach: to determine the rules of the species barrier on a molecular level in the test-tube.<p>

DR SUZETTE PRIOLA:  Evidence from other labs has suggested that
the type of PRP protein that an animal makes can determine whether or not that animal is going to be susceptible to infection with the agent from a different species So what we know is that this protein, this PRP protein, is, it's composed of a sequence of what are called amino acids which are linked in a long chain and that the amino acid sequence of PRP from an animal like a sheep differs from the sequence in an animal such as a cow and what we're interested in determining is if it's those differences between these two types of PRP that can affect whether or not this species barrier is broken and infection can occur.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  Dr Priola was intrigued by the puzzle of the species barrier between mice and hamsters.   <B>Although closely related and with similar PRP proteins, the hamster disease doesn't infect mice, but the mouse disease does infect hamsters. </B>She analysed the amino acid sequences of the mouse and the hamster prion proteins and swapped single amino acids to try to discover how many of them were controlling the species barrier.<p>

SUZETTE PRIOLA:  Between the mouse PRP and the hamster PRP there are 16 amino acid differences
and what we were able to do is show that you can control formation of this protein by changing just one amino acid, so one change out of 254 amino acids could be enough to allow the formation of this abnormal protein.  If you get the formation of this abnormal protein you're probably going to get disease. One of the things that this piece of work implies is that very minor changes in the PRP proteins between two different species could really have a dramatic effect on whether or not you get formation of this abnormal protein.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  With this discovery Dr. Priola had begun to decipher in the test-tube the complex rules of the species barrier, but although promising this is painstaking work, and it will be years before it can answer the key question about cows and humans. Meanwhile, a new scientific technique had been developed one which might at last indicate whether we would be susceptible to BSE.  Scientists had found a way to manufacture substitute humans: transgenic mice.<p>

<FONT COLOR="990099">JOHN COLLINGE</FONT>:  Transgenic mice are mice which contain a foreign gene that's been inserted into them
and you can make these mice by taking a single celled embryo, the fertilised egg from a mouse and injecting in DNA containing another gene. That can be a gene from another mouse, it can be a gene from another species.  In this way it's been possible to produce mice that make human prion protein, so there can now be a model, if you like, of a human being.  What we can do is inoculate these mice with BSE and see how susceptible they are to BSE and that may give us some idea about how effective the, the real species barrier is between cattle and humans.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  This work was begun in 1995, but before it could be completed the human experiment produced its first results.  In March 1996 the government announced that they believed the first humans had died of Mad Cow Disease.  Science had failed to find the answer in time.<p>

ADRIANO AGUZZI:  Like everybody else we were pretty shocked.  I mean everybody was thinking that there might be a theoretical risk of transmission of BSE to humans, but, but one thing is to say OK, there may be a theoretical risk,  another thing is to see patients dying from it, so, so this came as a, as a very sobering experience to us.<p>

<FONT COLOR="996633">DAVID TAYLOR</FONT>:  I'm on record as being of the opinion that BSE would not represent a risk to the human population.  I accept that I may have to revise that view in light of the             variant cases of CJD but of course we still have to wait and see to, to see if these really are associated with BSE.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FF3366">PAUL BROWN</FONT>:  If these 10 people have died from BSE then essentially the entire population of Britain is at risk.<p>

<FONT COLOR="FD3097">NARRATOR</FONT>:  In this warehouse in America brain samples are stored from victims of all human spongiform encephalopathies, including those from the only epidemic that we've ever known - kuru in Papua New Guinea.   Scientists are now debating whether we in Britain are heading for the second epidemic and how big that epidemic might be.  Tomorrow night Horizon asks who is at risk and how many may die.
