                                          Britain provides options for cattle-culling policy. Deciding which option to implement is
                                          another matter. 
                                        
                                       
                                         
<H3><CENTER>BSE 'will <A NAME="vanish">vanish</A> without culling'</CENTER></H3>

                  By Roger Highfield, Science Editor<BR>
Electronic Telegraph, 29 August 1996
<P>

<P>THE BSE epidemic in Britain will decline close to
extinction by the year 2001 and there is no scientific need for cattle
to be culled, new research suggests. The findings call into question the selective cull
of cattle older than 30 months, the main element   of the Government's efforts to restore confidence in
British beef. The study shows that only the obliteration of the
national herd could eradicate BSE sooner, an option already ruled out
by Britain and the EU. Using Ministry of Agriculture data, a team of
scientists predicts that there are 20,600 cattle with BSE and 6,950
will go on to be recorded as cases - 580 infected maternally and the
remainder from eating contaminated feed. There will be only 53
infected animals left in 2001.<P>

 
                  In the absence of a test that can spot BSE before
symptoms develop, the team's study, published today in Nature, shows
that it is not possible to make a big dent in numbers without
slaughtering whole herds. The number of infections from contaminated
feed fell after the feed ban and lingered until the end of 1994 when
the last of it was used up by farmers. The remaining new infections
are largely from maternal transmission. The number of new cases "will
fade close to extinction with no culling at all by the year 2000".<P>

  Can the disease be eradicated faster than under
existing policy? "The answer is no, without culling enormous numbers,"
said Prof Roy Anderson, of the Wellcome Trust, who led the
Government-approved research.  Hitting the target of a 150,000 cull - and tracing
offspring - increases the decline of the epidemic by about 20 per
cent. "We can improve on that, but not by a great deal," he said. "On
scientific grounds - if you are just considering BSE in cattle - then
there is a good argument for doing nothing. However, a human health
issue is involved, and public confidence has been severely damaged."

<hr>

<H3><CENTER>Whitehall urged to <A NAME="halt">halt</A> slaughter of 147,000 cattle</CENTER></H3>

                  By David Brown and Roger Highfield<BR>
Electronic Telegraph, 29 August 1996
<P>

 
                  THE results of a study of BSE, which show that the
epidemic will fade away even without a cattle cull, brought calls last
night for the Government to abandon plans to slaughter up to 147,000
selected animals.
 
                  The report by independent scientists concludes that
the Government was right in claiming that its existing policies were
sufficient to eliminate BSE by the turn of the century. The findings,
by the Wellcome Centre for the Epidemiology of Infectious Diseases at
Oxford University, vindicate the Government's control measures
including the compulsory slaughter of all suspect animals and the
banning of cattle food containing animal remains. This is believed to
have caused BSE in the first place.<P>

 
                  Last night the Government was urged to halt or
drastically amend plans to extend its cull - Europe's price for
reconsidering its export ban on British beef. The proposed cull, which
is fiercely opposed by vets, scientists and farmers, will come before
Parliament for approval in October and the latest evidence casts doubt
on whether MPs can support it. The beef export ban was imposed after
Stephen Dorrell, Health Secretary, announced on March 20 that BSE may
be linked to a new strain of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) - the
human equivalent of BSE.<P>
 
                  Measures to resolve the beef crisis, including the
destruction of cattle more than 30 months of age, is expected to cost
the taxpayer &2.5 billion over the next three years. The additional
extra cull of up to 147,000 targeted "high risk" cattle demanded by
Europe is expected to cost around &500 million but the exact figure is
unknown until exact compensation terms for farmers are fixed.<P>
 
                       'We compare the cull with the burning of
witches in days gone by'<P>
 
                  Labour called last night for Douglas Hogg, Minister
of Agriculture, to re-think the selective cull plans, although there
were no signs that he would. Dr Gavin Strang, shadow minister of
agriculture, said: "The only justification for Parliament going along
with a selective cull is the necessity to reach an agreement on
lifting the European export ban. I would strongly like to see the
Government make further efforts to secure another arrangement which
would bring about the lifting of the ban."<P>

 
                  Labour attacked the Government for not spending
enough on research to find a live diagnostic test for BSE. The report
pointed out pressure for cattle culls was due mainly to the absence of
such a test to positively identify cattle stricken by BSE. Currently,
BSE can be confirmed only by laboratory tests after suspect animals
are culled. Dr Strang said: "We are paying the price of a Government
that has cut the Ministry of Agriculture research budget by 40 per
cent since 1979."<P>

 
                  Francis Anthony, the British Veterinary
Association's spokesman on BSE, said: "The report vindicates what we
have been saying all along. The Government should now re-think its
selective culling policy which will kill too many healthy animals. We
compare the cull with the burning of witches in days gone by. It is
being done to placate a bunch of Eurocrats across the water, not for
scientific reasons. The epidemic is falling fast. Some vets hardly
come across a BSE cow nowadays."<P>

 
                  Sir David Naish, president of the National Farmers'
Union of England and Wales, said: "The selective cull scheme should be
re-examined but nothing must be done to jeopardise the lifting of the
export ban." Ministers refused to be drawn last night on whether
they would seek to abandon the selective cull policy.
<HR>

<H3><CENTER><A NAME="Total">Total</A> of infected animals was under-estimated</CENTER></H3>

 Electronic Telegraph, 29 August 1996
<P>
THE number of cattle that have been infected with
BSE is <B>six times greater than the cases confirmed</B> by the Government,
the study shows.
 
                  While official figures show that 161,412 cases of
the disease were confirmed by this summer, the Oxford University team
has used new mathematical methods to show that 900,000 cattle were
infected up to the end of last year. Most of the cattle ended up in
the food chain before symptoms of the disease developed. Prof Roy
Anderson, who led the team, said: "Using some quite sophisticated
computational techniques, we can back-calculate the total number of
infected animals and when they were infected." This number peaked at
300,000 new infections in 1987 and 900,000 overall.<P>

 
                  "The reason there is an enormous difference is that
most of those animals were slaughtered and went into the food chain
before BSE developed," he said. "Prior to the specified offal ban
in1989, 440,000 went into the food chain."
 
                  This is not such bad news as it sounds: studies on
mice show that the density of the prion disease agents is highest when
the symptoms develop. "Out of those 440,000, only 6,600 were in this
late stage," said Prof Anderson.<P>

 
                  The population would have been exposed to most of
the risk in 1988-89, consistent with the appearance of the new variant
of CJD in 1994 - but still not proof of a link, he said.
 
                  The new analysis draws on the link between dose and
the incubation time of the disease - <B>an oral dose of one gram of
diseased brain can cause the disease within five years</B>, while 100
grams can shrink this period to 32 months. "That dose-dependent
incubation period is very important because it gives us the shape of
the epidemic," said Prof Anderson.
<HR>
<H3><CENTER>Listserve Commentary</CENTER></H3>
29 August 1996
<P>

The ruminant feed ban came into force in 1988. But, many farmers
continued to use possibly contaminated feed until 1994, "when the last of
it was used up", according to Roger Highfield.
<P>
In June 1996 the Government announced fines and imprisonment for further
use of illegal animal feed. 5,000 fine for a first offence and one months
jail for a second.
<P>
That only 6,600 were in the late stage, doesn't mean that 433,400 BSE
infected animals went into the food chain - without being infectious.
Finally, 460,000 BSE infected cows and calves have entered the food chain after
the specified offal ban in 1989.
