</A> <H3><CENTER>Britain is preparing for a fresh BSE <A NAME="conflict">conflict</A> with EU members </CENTER></H3>

The Times: Britain: August 30 1996<BR>
BY ARTHUR LEATHLEY, MICHAEL HORNSBY AND CHARLES BREMNER
<P>

MINISTERS are preparing for a new conflict with Europe over "mad cow" disease in the wake of fresh evidence suggesting that it will die out naturally in Britain within five years.



The Government moved last night to head off a threatened Tory backbench revolt by suggesting that ministers would reopen negotiations with European partners over the planned cull of more than 120,000 cattle. Angela Browning, a junior Agriculture Minister, said that there was an urgent need to examine the culling policy in the light of the new research.

<P>

BSE, which, it is feared, might be linked to the human brain disease CJD, could disappear naturally by 2001, the research suggests. Mrs Browning seized on the findings, which support claims by farmers that a widescale cull is unnecessary. She said: "We need to take stock quite urgently of the implications of this evidence."

<P>

Tory backbenchers and farmers' leaders increased pressure on the Government to renegotiate the proposed cull that they claim would lead to the unnecessary deaths of thousands of uninfected cattle. Euro-sceptic MPs have warned ministers that they will oppose plans for the cull which have to be debated in the Commons after the summer recess, in October.

<P>

John Biffen, MP for Shropshire North, claimed that he would not vote for the current "needless" selective slaughter policy and called for the Government to change its cattle cull scheme in the light of new evidence that BSE would die out naturally within five years. Mr Biffen, speaking on BBC Radio 4's <I>World at One</I>, warned ministers of backbench unease over a cull based not on scientific advice, but on public sentiment.

<P>

Mrs Browning moved to defuse Euro-sceptic anger, saying: "I think we need to look at what has been a very useful, valuable piece of research, analyse it ... and then we need to take that information [to Europe]. We will obviously want to reopen discussions with our European partners and the Commission."

<P>

However, on the Continent the latest findings, combined with last month's evidence on cow-to-calf transmission of BSE, were seen as handing ammunition to Germany and other EU states which are intent on revising the plan for easing the beef ban which was agreed in Florence in June.

<P>

Officials in Brussels interpreted the research at Oxford University's zoology department as offering reasons for extending the cull. The finding that about 700,000 cattle incubating BSE had probably entered the food chain by the end of last year was considered to confirm that Britain had mishandled the epidemic and that British beef should be readmitted only when the disease had been eradicated.

<P>

Gerard Kiely, spokesman for the Commission's farm directorate, said it was most unlikely that the EU would consider reducing the cull. "We agreed [the cull] following detailed scientific analysis using a methodology which would take out the maximum number of BSE cases possible," he said. "I think it would be very difficult to sell to the Commission a programme which would involve the elimination of fewer BSE cases."
<HR>


<H3><CENTER><A NAME="Tough">Tough</A> questions for MAFF</CENTER></H3>
Listserve 31 Aug 1996
<P>

Had MAFF done the following, we would probably not have approx 900,000 BSE-cases, with more than 700,000 entering the food chain and a fear among people that have eaten potentially infected cattle for more than 10 years -- animals that should have been destroyed:
<PRE> 
* if the feed ban had been enforced in 1988
 
* if an entire herd had been destroyed when a BSE case was confirmed
 
* if many actions of 1995-96 had been taken in the late 80's instead</PRE>

<B>Questions on the delayed timing of MAFF regulatory actions:</B>
 
<PRE>Why was there a lack of "determination to shut off this major source of
infectivity once and for all" in 1988-89?
 
Why was possibly infectious ruminant feed not destroyed, but recycled in
feed mills,and fed to pigs and poultry?
 
Why weren't the stocks of feed "recalled, with compensation, being
collected and disposed of at Government expense" in 1988?
 
Why no requirement "to clean out storage facilities and equipment that may
have come in contact with MBM or feed containing it withing 48 hours" when
the feed ban came into force?
 
Shouldn't the compliance has been "ensured by State Veterinary Service
inspections" from day one?
 
Why didn't it become an offense immediately to use MBM, or have it "present
at farms, feed mills and feed merchants premises"?
 
The feed ban of '88 was a key instrument to control transmission of BSE.
So, why was it not enforced in 1988-89, but in 1996?<<HR>



